1
00:00:15,140 --> 00:00:18,009
(GBRB: Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)

2
00:00:18,010 --> 00:00:20,609
(Lee Kwang Soo)

3
00:00:20,610 --> 00:00:22,709
(Kim Woo Bin)

4
00:00:22,710 --> 00:00:24,949
(Doh Kyung Soo)

5
00:00:24,950 --> 00:00:28,050
(This program contains indirect advertisements.)

6
00:00:29,590 --> 00:00:31,860
(GBRB: Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)

7
00:00:32,190 --> 00:00:33,689
(KKPP versus Farm, Round 2 of yutnori)

8
00:00:33,690 --> 00:00:34,989
The four of us will do...

9
00:00:34,990 --> 00:00:36,829
the morning task tomorrow.

10
00:00:36,830 --> 00:00:39,160
(A game of yutnori with the next morning's work on the line)

11
00:00:39,660 --> 00:00:42,130
(Thanks to Kyung Soo's miraculous performance,)

12
00:00:42,570 --> 00:00:44,739
(KKPP claimed victory in Round 2.)

13
00:00:44,740 --> 00:00:46,469
(Final yutnori result: KKPP treats everyone to lunch.)

14
00:00:46,470 --> 00:00:48,170
(Exempt from the extra task of spreading out garlic peel)

15
00:00:48,870 --> 00:00:51,679
(Day 3 of their technical training, their last day at the dairy farm)

16
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:53,180
Why don't we divide the work?

17
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:56,079
(The trainees assign roles among themselves and become more skilled.)

18
00:00:56,080 --> 00:00:58,280
We're working faster than yesterday.

19
00:00:58,620 --> 00:01:01,650
(Just about to take a break after finishing the morning task early)

20
00:01:02,220 --> 00:01:03,589
- Kyung Soo, let's go.
- Okay.

21
00:01:03,590 --> 00:01:04,619
What are they?

22
00:01:04,620 --> 00:01:07,319
- Good job on the morning task.
- Thanks.

23
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:08,589
You're going to take a rest now.

24
00:01:08,590 --> 00:01:09,990
- Okay.
- But on your way...

25
00:01:10,900 --> 00:01:12,659
Could I ask you a favor?

26
00:01:12,660 --> 00:01:13,800
Sure.

27
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:15,300
So...

28
00:01:15,300 --> 00:01:16,300
(What favor?)

29
00:01:16,301 --> 00:01:18,670
From the milk our cows produce...

30
00:01:19,240 --> 00:01:21,739
on the farm, we make things like yogurt.

31
00:01:21,740 --> 00:01:22,839
I see.

32
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:24,879
We supply them at local grocery stores...

33
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:27,040
- and cafes.
- Okay.

34
00:01:27,580 --> 00:01:29,980
I'd like to ask you to help...

35
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:31,080
- with the deliveries.
- Delivery?

36
00:01:31,081 --> 00:01:32,480
- Delivery? I see.
- That's right.

37
00:01:32,550 --> 00:01:34,690
- Take a look here.
- Do you supply milk too?

38
00:01:35,390 --> 00:01:38,090
(He opens his bag and looks for something.)

39
00:01:38,420 --> 00:01:40,659
I brought it while I was at the warehouse.

40
00:01:40,660 --> 00:01:42,460
What is it? Is it cheese?

41
00:01:42,930 --> 00:01:44,129
- Thank you.
- It's string cheese.

42
00:01:44,130 --> 00:01:45,130
That's right.

43
00:01:45,131 --> 00:01:46,699
(Excited about the food gift)

44
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:48,600
- I really love it.
- Get their signature and...

45
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:50,169
I always buy it whenever I go to the convenience store.

46
00:01:50,170 --> 00:01:51,599
This is the same.

47
00:01:51,600 --> 00:01:52,600
(He couldn't wait and opened it right away.)

48
00:01:52,601 --> 00:01:54,510
Please deliver this to the cafe.

49
00:01:54,770 --> 00:01:55,969
Get their signature...

50
00:01:55,970 --> 00:01:57,979
- and bring half of the page.
- Okay.

51
00:01:57,980 --> 00:02:00,009
This one is simple.

52
00:02:00,010 --> 00:02:01,380
(The CEO and intern are distracted by the cheese.)

53
00:02:02,480 --> 00:02:06,679
And there will be some leftovers.

54
00:02:06,680 --> 00:02:08,289
(He picks one piece of cheese...)

55
00:02:08,290 --> 00:02:09,290
(and takes a bite.)

56
00:02:09,291 --> 00:02:11,959
If you subtract the leftover from 20,

57
00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:13,289
- My goodness.
- it will be...

58
00:02:13,290 --> 00:02:14,290
(Exclaiming)

59
00:02:14,390 --> 00:02:15,989
This is always used...

60
00:02:15,990 --> 00:02:17,259
- It's so good.
- Yes.

61
00:02:17,260 --> 00:02:19,459
So there are 20 each.

62
00:02:19,460 --> 00:02:21,269
We collect back anything that doesn't get sold.

63
00:02:21,270 --> 00:02:24,499
Because the customers should not eat the spoiled one.

64
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:27,070
(Even the Food Director takes a moment to savor the taste.)

65
00:02:27,470 --> 00:02:29,369
Everything I thought was string cheese until now...

66
00:02:29,370 --> 00:02:30,469
wasn't real string cheese.

67
00:02:30,470 --> 00:02:32,379
(There he goes again.)

68
00:02:32,380 --> 00:02:33,640
How is this so good?

69
00:02:35,850 --> 00:02:37,979
(Delighted by how good it is)

70
00:02:37,980 --> 00:02:40,749
- This would make an amazing pizza.
- Put 20 of them...

71
00:02:40,750 --> 00:02:43,050
(Three people eating, one person working)

72
00:02:43,450 --> 00:02:44,620
Can you give me a bite?

73
00:02:45,220 --> 00:02:47,860
(After completing the takeover, the auditor finally gets a bite.)

74
00:02:48,330 --> 00:02:49,430
Gosh, it's so good.

75
00:02:50,190 --> 00:02:51,600
(After tasting the cheese)

76
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:53,699
We'll get going now.

77
00:02:53,700 --> 00:02:54,700
(The trainees head out to deliver.)

78
00:02:54,701 --> 00:02:55,829
(Current time: 10am)

79
00:02:55,830 --> 00:02:58,269
(First, they're on their way to deliver to a cafe.)

80
00:02:58,270 --> 00:02:59,670
Sang Hoon, are you really hungry?

81
00:02:59,900 --> 00:03:01,040
I'm running out of energy.

82
00:03:01,570 --> 00:03:04,310
(The trainees have been working since dawn and haven't eaten yet.)

83
00:03:04,910 --> 00:03:06,539
We're on our way...

84
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:08,180
- to make deliveries.
- Yes.

85
00:03:08,650 --> 00:03:10,950
If we make the deliveries and stop somewhere to eat...

86
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:12,950
Will we have enough time?

87
00:03:13,380 --> 00:03:14,850
How about this?

88
00:03:15,320 --> 00:03:16,650
Let's make the deliveries first.

89
00:03:16,750 --> 00:03:19,320
I heard there's a brick oven at the farm,

90
00:03:20,060 --> 00:03:21,860
so we could make something there.

91
00:03:22,360 --> 00:03:24,830
Like pizza since we have cheese.

92
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:29,929
Do you want to make something with cheese at the farm?

93
00:03:29,930 --> 00:03:31,669
(They plan to skip breakfast and make lunch with the brick oven.)

94
00:03:31,670 --> 00:03:33,299
- So...
- As brunch?

95
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:34,370
Yes.

96
00:03:35,340 --> 00:03:36,809
We can eat lunch at the farm,

97
00:03:36,810 --> 00:03:38,340
but we're a bit hungry now.

98
00:03:38,940 --> 00:03:41,009
Let's stop by a bakery and get some bread.

99
00:03:41,010 --> 00:03:42,049
Let's get some bread.

100
00:03:42,050 --> 00:03:43,880
- That's a great idea.
- So we can eat something.

101
00:03:45,380 --> 00:03:46,779
- We're here.
- The cafe is over there.

102
00:03:46,780 --> 00:03:49,089
That's the cafe. The word "coffee" is written there.

103
00:03:49,090 --> 00:03:50,090
(They arrive at the cafe.)

104
00:03:50,650 --> 00:03:52,390
We're here.

105
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:53,860
Please get out.

106
00:03:54,690 --> 00:03:56,660
That should be the one with ten.

107
00:03:56,760 --> 00:03:57,760
(Taking the yogurt to deliver)

108
00:03:57,760 --> 00:03:58,760
Okay.

109
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:01,129
- Hello.
- Hello.

110
00:04:01,130 --> 00:04:02,370
- Hello.
- Hello.

111
00:04:02,470 --> 00:04:04,600
We're here to deliver some yogurt.

112
00:04:05,670 --> 00:04:07,169
- Here you go.
- Okay.

113
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:08,370
(Delivering yogurt to the cafe)

114
00:04:08,910 --> 00:04:10,940
We have things to collect back, don't we?

115
00:04:11,610 --> 00:04:13,780
Don't we have returns to pick up?

116
00:04:14,210 --> 00:04:15,379
No, there aren't any returns.

117
00:04:15,380 --> 00:04:17,150
We're using all of them,

118
00:04:17,310 --> 00:04:18,379
so there isn't anything to return.

119
00:04:18,380 --> 00:04:19,380
- So we can just go?
- Yes.

120
00:04:19,381 --> 00:04:21,789
- I see. Is that good news?
- Thank you.

121
00:04:21,790 --> 00:04:22,790
- It means they're selling well.
- Exactly.

122
00:04:22,791 --> 00:04:23,949
I see.

123
00:04:23,950 --> 00:04:25,359
We've never had a single return.

124
00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:26,759
(Feeling proud that everything sells out)

125
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:28,560
- Thank you.
- It gets sold out.

126
00:04:29,330 --> 00:04:30,429
Yesterday,

127
00:04:30,430 --> 00:04:32,000
- we milked the cows ourselves.
- Really?

128
00:04:32,060 --> 00:04:33,429
That's great.

129
00:04:33,430 --> 00:04:35,530
To be more precise,

130
00:04:35,870 --> 00:04:37,369
only the three of us worked yesterday.

131
00:04:37,370 --> 00:04:39,769
Sang Hoon got here late.

132
00:04:39,770 --> 00:04:41,539
- He arrived yesterday afternoon.
- I see.

133
00:04:41,540 --> 00:04:43,510
So the three of us made it.

134
00:04:43,810 --> 00:04:45,739
- Oh, thank you.
- Sure.

135
00:04:45,740 --> 00:04:46,740
(The CEO draws a firm line.)

136
00:04:47,240 --> 00:04:49,009
- We'll get going.
- Goodbye.

137
00:04:49,010 --> 00:04:50,609
- Thank you.
- Have a good day.

138
00:04:50,610 --> 00:04:51,620
Bye.

139
00:04:52,650 --> 00:04:55,119
(They arrive at a grocery store, the second delivery stop.)

140
00:04:55,120 --> 00:04:57,249
Do you know those peanut cream buns they sell...

141
00:04:57,250 --> 00:04:58,920
at the grocery store bakery?

142
00:04:59,290 --> 00:05:00,960
- And mammoth bread?
- Yes.

143
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:03,060
- Those are delicious.
- I love that bread.

144
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:04,300
The classic ones.

145
00:05:06,230 --> 00:05:07,869
Which way do we go?

146
00:05:07,870 --> 00:05:09,430
Kwang Soo, there's Tous les Jours bakery.

147
00:05:09,530 --> 00:05:10,530
Right.

148
00:05:10,531 --> 00:05:11,540
(They spot the bakery as soon as they walk in.)

149
00:05:12,940 --> 00:05:14,969
(As if hypnotized, he heads somewhere.)

150
00:05:14,970 --> 00:05:17,469
Let's make the delivery first. He said that we had our own shelf.

151
00:05:17,470 --> 00:05:19,080
Are those vegetable dinner rolls?

152
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:21,079
Did you know that they disappeared?

153
00:05:21,080 --> 00:05:22,150
We used to have them as kids.

154
00:05:22,250 --> 00:05:23,509
With vegetable bits inside.

155
00:05:23,510 --> 00:05:24,579
I don't know them.

156
00:05:24,580 --> 00:05:26,019
It's a type of dinner roll.

157
00:05:26,020 --> 00:05:27,750
Sweet dinner rolls...

158
00:05:27,850 --> 00:05:29,620
No, there are vegetable dinner rolls.

159
00:05:30,090 --> 00:05:32,060
(The hungry intern can't stop talking about food.)

160
00:05:32,460 --> 00:05:33,490
Delivery?

161
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:36,159
He said that we had our own shelf.

162
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:37,329
- Our own shelf?
- Yes.

163
00:05:37,330 --> 00:05:39,399
- Hello.
- Hello.

164
00:05:39,400 --> 00:05:41,499
Excuse me, but where can we find yogurt?

165
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:42,500
- Yogurt?
- Yes.

166
00:05:42,501 --> 00:05:44,999
Take the escalator. You'll find it on the second floor.

167
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:46,199
On the second floor? Thank you.

168
00:05:46,200 --> 00:05:47,239
Thank you.

169
00:05:47,240 --> 00:05:48,240
(They head up to the 2nd floor.)

170
00:05:49,370 --> 00:05:50,970
Woo Bin.

171
00:05:51,380 --> 00:05:53,040
If we're going to cook something later,

172
00:05:53,810 --> 00:05:55,379
- Get groceries here?
- we can buy the ingredients here.

173
00:05:55,380 --> 00:05:56,450
That's a good idea.

174
00:05:56,810 --> 00:05:59,320
(They decide to shop for lunch after finishing the delivery.)

175
00:05:59,980 --> 00:06:02,190
What would be good to cook in a brick oven?

176
00:06:02,920 --> 00:06:04,390
Wood-fired pizza.

177
00:06:04,690 --> 00:06:06,920
May I ask you something?

178
00:06:07,390 --> 00:06:09,260
If it's possible,

179
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:11,159
how about making curry and dipping naan in it?

180
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:12,300
- Oh, my.
- That sounds good.

181
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:13,400
I can definitely make...

182
00:06:13,401 --> 00:06:14,430
- curry.
- That sounds so good.

183
00:06:15,430 --> 00:06:16,430
That sounds really good.

184
00:06:16,431 --> 00:06:17,700
(The intern seems confident about making curry.)

185
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:19,370
- Here they are.
- Right.

186
00:06:19,640 --> 00:06:21,640
(They decide to finish the delivery first.)

187
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:23,469
We can put them in the back.

188
00:06:23,470 --> 00:06:25,240
Wait, I need to check the inventory.

189
00:06:25,740 --> 00:06:27,780
One, two, three.

190
00:06:28,210 --> 00:06:30,379
(Woo Bin checks the inventory.)

191
00:06:30,380 --> 00:06:33,120
He said that we needed to collect these back.

192
00:06:33,580 --> 00:06:34,789
- We need to collect them back?
- I think we should take them out.

193
00:06:34,790 --> 00:06:35,790
Yes.

194
00:06:35,790 --> 00:06:36,790
Hello.

195
00:06:36,791 --> 00:06:39,019
We're going to pick up the yogurt and restock the shelf.

196
00:06:39,020 --> 00:06:40,689
- Gosh, hello.
- Hello.

197
00:06:40,690 --> 00:06:42,659
- Can we take these?
- Yes.

198
00:06:42,660 --> 00:06:43,929
We'll take the remainder...

199
00:06:43,930 --> 00:06:45,259
- and replace them...
- Yes.

200
00:06:45,260 --> 00:06:46,299
- with new ones.
- We'll restock them.

201
00:06:46,300 --> 00:06:47,729
Please leave what you brought.

202
00:06:47,730 --> 00:06:48,799
- Really?
- Yes.

203
00:06:48,800 --> 00:06:50,299
Okay. We got it.

204
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:51,799
The ones in the front aren't the same brand, right?

205
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:52,869
- No, they are not.
- No.

206
00:06:52,870 --> 00:06:56,870
Would it be okay if we moved them?

207
00:06:59,010 --> 00:07:00,180
- That's a good idea.
- To the front...

208
00:07:01,150 --> 00:07:04,180
I'm sorry, but our brand should be placed...

209
00:07:04,580 --> 00:07:05,580
in the front.

210
00:07:05,581 --> 00:07:08,320
(Hoping their products would stand out a little more)

211
00:07:08,990 --> 00:07:11,260
I apologize to the other sellers, but it can't be helped.

212
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:15,530
It'd be better to create a boundary.

213
00:07:16,490 --> 00:07:18,800
Someone might end up buying another brand instead.

214
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:20,960
Should I place them like this?

215
00:07:21,730 --> 00:07:24,229
(Hoping their products stand out more)

216
00:07:24,230 --> 00:07:26,600
It'd be nice if we could mist it with a spray.

217
00:07:27,970 --> 00:07:29,109
Like in a commercial.

218
00:07:29,110 --> 00:07:30,110
(Wanting to do anything they could to help)

219
00:07:30,111 --> 00:07:31,580
Looking at the label makes you...

220
00:07:31,680 --> 00:07:32,710
want to buy it.

221
00:07:32,980 --> 00:07:35,510
(After finishing the second delivery with lots of care)

222
00:07:35,710 --> 00:07:38,019
Sang Hoon, please make us curry this time.

223
00:07:38,020 --> 00:07:39,020
What do you think about curry?

224
00:07:39,020 --> 00:07:40,020
I love curry.

225
00:07:40,021 --> 00:07:41,149
- I like it too.
- It's my favorite.

226
00:07:41,150 --> 00:07:43,049
- It just needs rice.
- Right.

227
00:07:43,050 --> 00:07:44,050
(Menu Number 1: Intern Moon's signature curry)

228
00:07:44,051 --> 00:07:45,860
I'll look up how to make naan.

229
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:47,859
As long as it's not too hard...

230
00:07:47,860 --> 00:07:48,860
- Shall we just try it?
- I'll look it up.

231
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:49,860
Let's make it work.

232
00:07:50,490 --> 00:07:51,530
That sounds good, Sang Hoon.

233
00:07:51,860 --> 00:07:54,100
(Looking up how to make naan)

234
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:56,400
If we make naan,

235
00:07:56,470 --> 00:07:59,239
we could top it with tomato sauce and cheese,

236
00:07:59,240 --> 00:08:00,869
- and pop it into the brick oven.
- That's an option.

237
00:08:00,870 --> 00:08:02,910
(Menu Number 2: Wood-fired pizza)

238
00:08:03,640 --> 00:08:05,739
(Before deciding on the menu, they ask the farm seniors.)

239
00:08:05,740 --> 00:08:07,379
- Hello?
- Hello, Mr. Kkalloo.

240
00:08:07,380 --> 00:08:08,950
Hello, Mr. Kkalloo. This is CEO Lee.

241
00:08:09,610 --> 00:08:10,610
I'm sorry?

242
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:12,920
This is CEO Lee.

243
00:08:13,180 --> 00:08:14,180
Oh, hello.

244
00:08:14,181 --> 00:08:17,860
We're thinking of having...

245
00:08:18,190 --> 00:08:22,729
naan and curry for lunch.

246
00:08:22,730 --> 00:08:24,560
What do you think?

247
00:08:24,660 --> 00:08:26,800
Do whatever works best for you.

248
00:08:27,460 --> 00:08:29,800
What does Mr. Lal think?

249
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:33,499
Lal would like that too.

250
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:34,910
Can you make them?

251
00:08:35,870 --> 00:08:37,710
We've never tried, but we'll give it a try.

252
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:40,280
I see. Okay, CEO Lee.

253
00:08:42,480 --> 00:08:43,680
Did you just laugh at us?

254
00:08:44,350 --> 00:08:45,580
What? No.

255
00:08:46,450 --> 00:08:49,790
Once we finish the deliveries, we'll head back.

256
00:08:49,890 --> 00:08:52,220
- See you soon.
- Bye.

257
00:08:53,990 --> 00:08:56,429
I think I can make it.

258
00:08:56,430 --> 00:08:57,629
- Really?
- Yes.

259
00:08:57,630 --> 00:08:58,859
(Today's chef has found his confidence.)

260
00:08:58,860 --> 00:09:00,330
On top of that, it requires plain yogurt.

261
00:09:00,430 --> 00:09:01,929
- We can use...
- Seriously?

262
00:09:01,930 --> 00:09:03,199
- what we take back.
- You can use this.

263
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:04,670
(The yogurt is already set.)

264
00:09:04,900 --> 00:09:07,169
I'll walk you through the ingredients.

265
00:09:07,170 --> 00:09:08,940
Two cups of flour, plain yogurt,

266
00:09:09,040 --> 00:09:10,839
warm water, yeast.

267
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:12,140
We can buy yeast here.

268
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:15,450
I can stretch it out like this and put it together.

269
00:09:15,850 --> 00:09:17,450
Let's hurry and buy the ingredients.

270
00:09:17,650 --> 00:09:18,650
Okay.

271
00:09:18,650 --> 00:09:19,650
(Grocery shopping begins under Chef Moon's lead.)

272
00:09:19,980 --> 00:09:21,589
What type of flour is it? All-purpose flour?

273
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:23,490
It must be either bread flour or all-purpose flour.

274
00:09:24,050 --> 00:09:26,490
- All-purpose flour.
- One all-purpose flour.

275
00:09:26,890 --> 00:09:28,060
And yeast.

276
00:09:28,630 --> 00:09:30,130
It should be somewhere around here.

277
00:09:31,800 --> 00:09:33,460
(They quickly grab the yeast.)

278
00:09:34,770 --> 00:09:35,770
Tomato sauce.

279
00:09:35,771 --> 00:09:37,530
Wild arugula.

280
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:39,700
These look so good.

281
00:09:39,940 --> 00:09:41,809
One pack of chicken thighs and one pack of chicken breast.

282
00:09:41,810 --> 00:09:43,639
There are 2 farm owners and 1 CEO.

283
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:44,640
All right.

284
00:09:44,641 --> 00:09:46,110
Do we need 1 or 2 of these?

285
00:09:46,640 --> 00:09:47,909
I'll get 1kg.

286
00:09:47,910 --> 00:09:50,710
We're making curry for 12 servings.

287
00:09:51,110 --> 00:09:53,380
I'll use twice as many potatoes as carrots.

288
00:09:53,950 --> 00:09:55,590
(2kg of potatoes)

289
00:09:56,220 --> 00:09:57,990
(Onions)

290
00:09:58,190 --> 00:09:59,290
Is that all?

291
00:09:59,790 --> 00:10:01,660
Carrots, onions, potatoes.

292
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:03,160
Aren't these enough?

293
00:10:03,990 --> 00:10:05,959
(Lastly, Chef Moon is picking out the curry powder.)

294
00:10:05,960 --> 00:10:06,960
Are two enough?

295
00:10:07,330 --> 00:10:09,229
Two packs and this.

296
00:10:09,230 --> 00:10:11,030
- How about slightly spicy?
- That sounds great.

297
00:10:11,570 --> 00:10:12,839
(The secret is layering the curry flavor.)

298
00:10:12,840 --> 00:10:14,709
So you mix different kinds of curry.

299
00:10:14,710 --> 00:10:15,710
Yes.

300
00:10:16,140 --> 00:10:17,709
Aren't you pretending...

301
00:10:17,710 --> 00:10:19,309
- No.
- like you have your own recipe?

302
00:10:19,310 --> 00:10:20,979
- It seems like it.
- Caramel...

303
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:23,280
Shall I make caramel onions?

304
00:10:24,180 --> 00:10:25,979
- Caramel onions?
- Caramelized onions.

305
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:27,180
That sounds good.

306
00:10:28,050 --> 00:10:29,789
Actually, that takes a lot of work.

307
00:10:29,790 --> 00:10:31,220
You're good at cooking, aren't you?

308
00:10:31,420 --> 00:10:34,259
No, I can only make curry. That's my one signature dish.

309
00:10:34,260 --> 00:10:36,429
Instead of making rice...

310
00:10:36,430 --> 00:10:37,589
Let's make rice too.

311
00:10:37,590 --> 00:10:38,599
- Shall we?
- Yes.

312
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:41,770
First, over medium-low heat,

313
00:10:41,970 --> 00:10:44,100
you keep stirring the onions for about 15 minutes.

314
00:10:44,430 --> 00:10:46,040
They eventually turn brown.

315
00:10:46,370 --> 00:10:47,470
Once they turn brown,

316
00:10:47,740 --> 00:10:50,470
they give the sweetness and flavor.

317
00:10:50,570 --> 00:10:52,380
You keep stir-frying them...

318
00:10:53,940 --> 00:10:58,150
until they reach that brown color.

319
00:11:03,490 --> 00:11:05,689
When the onions turn brown,

320
00:11:05,690 --> 00:11:08,330
you add chopped chicken thighs.

321
00:11:09,490 --> 00:11:11,660
Then you add the curry powder.

322
00:11:12,760 --> 00:11:15,770
(In the end, the full recipe remained a secret.)

323
00:11:16,330 --> 00:11:17,600
We're getting fishcake, right?

324
00:11:18,240 --> 00:11:19,670
(They found a fishcake stand on their way out.)

325
00:11:19,900 --> 00:11:21,200
Let's have some.

326
00:11:21,540 --> 00:11:22,709
Hello.

327
00:11:22,710 --> 00:11:23,710
(They settle for a quick bite.)

328
00:11:23,711 --> 00:11:25,580
Gosh, they look delicious.

329
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:28,380
Why don't we get two rice cake ones? We can take a bite each.

330
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:30,010
Let's get two rice cake fishcakes.

331
00:11:30,110 --> 00:11:31,149
(Ordering 2 rice cake fishcakes)

332
00:11:31,150 --> 00:11:32,920
- Two rice cake fishcakes, please.
- Two?

333
00:11:33,020 --> 00:11:34,249
- Could you cut them?
- Yes.

334
00:11:34,250 --> 00:11:35,290
In half.

335
00:11:37,290 --> 00:11:38,589
(2 rice cake fishcakes into 4 pieces)

336
00:11:38,590 --> 00:11:39,860
We'll eat them here.

337
00:11:40,690 --> 00:11:41,990
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

338
00:11:43,890 --> 00:11:44,929
Go ahead and eat.

339
00:11:44,930 --> 00:11:46,629
(Their first bite after a long morning without food)

340
00:11:46,630 --> 00:11:48,200
Shall we eat together in the count of three?

341
00:11:48,730 --> 00:11:49,930
One, two, three.

342
00:11:51,370 --> 00:11:54,370
(How is their first bite?)

343
00:11:56,840 --> 00:11:58,510
(The deeply touching first bite)

344
00:11:58,610 --> 00:12:00,940
I'm glad that we didn't get any sauce.

345
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:02,510
It tastes so good.

346
00:12:03,150 --> 00:12:04,780
- Your fishcakes are excellent.
- I agree.

347
00:12:04,920 --> 00:12:07,050
(They taste even better on an empty stomach.)

348
00:12:07,580 --> 00:12:09,489
(Cleaning up)

349
00:12:09,490 --> 00:12:11,049
This is just a question.

350
00:12:11,050 --> 00:12:12,660
- Is the chili fishcake spicy?
- This is just a question.

351
00:12:13,190 --> 00:12:14,489
How about getting one chili fishcake...

352
00:12:14,490 --> 00:12:15,830
and dividing it in four?

353
00:12:16,490 --> 00:12:18,600
- Into four pieces.
- That sounds great.

354
00:12:18,860 --> 00:12:20,099
- Aren't you curious about it?
- I'm also in.

355
00:12:20,100 --> 00:12:22,570
Okay. Sir, can we get one chili fishcake?

356
00:12:22,770 --> 00:12:24,430
(Curiosity gets the better of them, so they order more.)

357
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:26,369
It's really delicious.

358
00:12:26,370 --> 00:12:28,210
(1 chili fishcake gets ready in no time.)

359
00:12:29,340 --> 00:12:30,340
One, two, three.

360
00:12:30,341 --> 00:12:32,040
(Eating the 3rd fishcake just like the 1st)

361
00:12:33,380 --> 00:12:35,579
The chili fishcake is better.

362
00:12:35,580 --> 00:12:38,009
- This was it.
- Yes, it tastes better.

363
00:12:38,010 --> 00:12:40,879
- It's the right amount of spicy.
- Nice and spicy.

364
00:12:40,880 --> 00:12:41,890
(Just enough spice to whet the appetite)

365
00:12:42,350 --> 00:12:44,859
Crab sticks are similar to fishcakes, right?

366
00:12:44,860 --> 00:12:46,890
But is a crab stick fishcake different?

367
00:12:47,290 --> 00:12:49,159
(A question conveniently leading to his next target)

368
00:12:49,160 --> 00:12:50,759
Let's just get one more and stop.

369
00:12:50,760 --> 00:12:51,760
All right.

370
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:53,330
(They're about to order one more.)

371
00:12:53,700 --> 00:12:54,930
It's 10 dollars for 5.

372
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:57,370
- How many did we eat so far?
- Three.

373
00:12:57,530 --> 00:12:59,500
Should we also get a sesame leaf fishcake?

374
00:13:00,470 --> 00:13:02,939
It's the same price, but you get one extra.

375
00:13:02,940 --> 00:13:03,970
Right.

376
00:13:04,810 --> 00:13:07,639
Then let's get 1 sesame leaf and 1 crab stick.

377
00:13:07,640 --> 00:13:08,979
Please cut them into four pieces each.

378
00:13:08,980 --> 00:13:09,980
On this plate.

379
00:13:11,250 --> 00:13:14,620
I can never resist 5 for 10-dollar deals.

380
00:13:16,520 --> 00:13:17,520
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

381
00:13:17,521 --> 00:13:18,720
The crab stick one looks so...

382
00:13:19,690 --> 00:13:21,320
Take the crab stick fishcake.

383
00:13:22,260 --> 00:13:23,389
(Hesitating)

384
00:13:23,390 --> 00:13:24,659
- Have some.
- I'll pick...

385
00:13:24,660 --> 00:13:26,500
- after Woo Bin.
- Just pick one.

386
00:13:26,600 --> 00:13:29,270
Woo Bin, pick one of the crab stick pieces.

387
00:13:29,730 --> 00:13:30,970
Do you like the ends?

388
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:32,940
Yes.

389
00:13:34,370 --> 00:13:36,709
You should take the bigger piece.

390
00:13:36,710 --> 00:13:38,310
Which one do you want, Sang Hoon?

391
00:13:42,080 --> 00:13:44,010
(The bigger piece)

392
00:13:45,380 --> 00:13:46,520
Go ahead.

393
00:13:47,920 --> 00:13:50,089
(A piece of crab stick fishcake)

394
00:13:50,090 --> 00:13:51,149
One, two, three.

395
00:13:51,150 --> 00:13:53,320
(A piece of sesame leaf fishcake)

396
00:13:53,390 --> 00:13:55,189
- This tastes mild.
- It's good.

397
00:13:55,190 --> 00:13:56,190
It tastes mild.

398
00:13:56,290 --> 00:13:57,560
- Thank you, sir.
- Thank you.

399
00:13:58,130 --> 00:14:00,500
This supermarket is a little dangerous,

400
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:01,930
don't you think?

401
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:06,340
We can't seem to walk past anything.

402
00:14:06,470 --> 00:14:07,639
(Was this a sign of things to come?)

403
00:14:07,640 --> 00:14:08,909
Do you agree with him?

404
00:14:08,910 --> 00:14:12,180
When you press bar rice cakes into sesame oil soy sauce,

405
00:14:12,310 --> 00:14:14,609
they get flat and spring back while soaking up the soy sauce.

406
00:14:14,610 --> 00:14:15,950
- I know what you mean.
- The sauce gets absorbed.

407
00:14:16,380 --> 00:14:18,179
Like a sponge when washing dishes...

408
00:14:18,180 --> 00:14:19,180
Yes.

409
00:14:19,380 --> 00:14:21,750
Gosh, it looks like nurungji.

410
00:14:22,220 --> 00:14:23,290
Kwang Soo, let's get this.

411
00:14:23,690 --> 00:14:25,059
It's crispy on the outside and moist on the inside.

412
00:14:25,060 --> 00:14:26,060
Seriously.

413
00:14:26,560 --> 00:14:28,160
Shouldn't we try a croffle too?

414
00:14:28,560 --> 00:14:30,590
- Kwang Soo, let's get it next time.
- Ten of these...

415
00:14:30,860 --> 00:14:31,860
We'll get it next time.

416
00:14:32,130 --> 00:14:33,400
Shouldn't we at least taste it?

417
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:36,370
One apple croffle, please.

418
00:14:37,100 --> 00:14:38,939
We need to get some walnut balls.

419
00:14:38,940 --> 00:14:40,740
(Their appetite keeps growing endlessly.)

420
00:14:40,970 --> 00:14:43,640
- Hello.
- Aren't we going to Tous les Jours?

421
00:14:44,370 --> 00:14:46,240
We came here originally for bread.

422
00:14:47,810 --> 00:14:49,309
Sang Hoon, aren't we going to Tous les Jours?

423
00:14:49,310 --> 00:14:50,310
Tous les Jours?

424
00:14:50,850 --> 00:14:53,350
Ever since I was a kid, my wish was to eat this as much as I wanted.

425
00:14:53,550 --> 00:14:55,490
Do you want to make that wish come true today?

426
00:14:57,120 --> 00:14:59,090
Did you know that twisted donuts are good with ketchup?

427
00:14:59,420 --> 00:15:00,760
Doesn't it look like a baby's bottom?

428
00:15:01,660 --> 00:15:02,860
- It looks so good.
- You're right.

429
00:15:03,360 --> 00:15:05,200
If it's rich milk bread, we must get it.

430
00:15:05,760 --> 00:15:07,059
- Sesame seed glutinous rice bread.
- Sesame seed glutinous rice bread.

431
00:15:07,060 --> 00:15:08,469
- This is really good.
- Totally.

432
00:15:08,470 --> 00:15:10,299
I like tearing out the soft inside of this bread,

433
00:15:10,300 --> 00:15:12,069
rolling it into balls, and eating it.

434
00:15:12,070 --> 00:15:13,070
I know what you mean.

435
00:15:13,340 --> 00:15:14,539
- You can do that with toast bread.
- Right.

436
00:15:14,540 --> 00:15:16,670
(Did you make your wish come true?)

437
00:15:16,840 --> 00:15:19,510
Honestly, I don't think these are just food.

438
00:15:19,810 --> 00:15:21,539
They're closer to souvenirs.

439
00:15:21,540 --> 00:15:22,550
Here you go, Sang Hoon.

440
00:15:24,880 --> 00:15:25,980
It's really good.

441
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:30,749
Honestly, I wanted to stop eating after two pieces of fishcake.

442
00:15:30,750 --> 00:15:31,820
Really?

443
00:15:32,620 --> 00:15:34,419
I wanted to stop you guys,

444
00:15:34,420 --> 00:15:36,760
but even you got pulled in.

445
00:15:37,190 --> 00:15:39,560
I lost control before I even realized it.

446
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:42,870
(The auditor was slowly won over by the CEO and the intern.)

447
00:15:43,130 --> 00:15:44,369
Look at them.

448
00:15:44,370 --> 00:15:46,040
They're eating even during the interview

449
00:15:46,540 --> 00:15:48,609
(You're a perfect match.)

450
00:15:48,610 --> 00:15:49,670
I'm not sure.

451
00:15:52,080 --> 00:15:54,179
- We just found our rhythm.
- We played a piece of music.

452
00:15:54,180 --> 00:15:55,749
I was improvising in a jam session.

453
00:15:55,750 --> 00:15:58,820
It felt like our chords naturally fell into place.

454
00:15:59,180 --> 00:16:00,749
He's the guide I've been searching for.

455
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:02,920
He shows me the direction.

456
00:16:03,350 --> 00:16:04,849
I can't open my eyes when I swim.

457
00:16:04,850 --> 00:16:07,259
While I'm swimming with my eyes closed,

458
00:16:07,260 --> 00:16:09,630
CEO Lee seems to guide me in the right direction.

459
00:16:10,030 --> 00:16:11,030
Here's why.

460
00:16:11,860 --> 00:16:14,400
I can't swim, but I can see where I'm going.

461
00:16:14,800 --> 00:16:17,400
I can't see what's ahead, but I know how to swim.

462
00:16:17,970 --> 00:16:20,100
(Their teamwork and chemistry are incredible.)

463
00:16:20,340 --> 00:16:21,340
What's that called?

464
00:16:21,341 --> 00:16:22,939
The upper body is human,

465
00:16:22,940 --> 00:16:24,010
but the legs are a horse.

466
00:16:24,470 --> 00:16:25,980
- A centaur?
- Yes.

467
00:16:26,210 --> 00:16:28,650
If we became a centaur,

468
00:16:28,950 --> 00:16:32,120
I'd gladly give Sang Hoon the upper body.

469
00:16:33,820 --> 00:16:34,920
I'd spend my whole life...

470
00:16:35,590 --> 00:16:36,590
pooping.

471
00:16:37,120 --> 00:16:38,420
I'd let Sang Hoon handle...

472
00:16:39,120 --> 00:16:40,220
eating good food, talking,

473
00:16:40,620 --> 00:16:42,630
and everything else.

474
00:16:43,730 --> 00:16:45,799
My parents gave birth to me,

475
00:16:45,800 --> 00:16:47,860
but CEO Lee is the one who truly understands me.

476
00:16:53,600 --> 00:16:56,570
(GBRB Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)

477
00:16:56,670 --> 00:16:59,139
(Lee Kwang Soo)

478
00:16:59,140 --> 00:17:01,339
(Kim Woo Bin)

479
00:17:01,340 --> 00:17:03,510
(Doh Kyung Soo)

480
00:17:08,150 --> 00:17:10,450
(GBRB Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)

481
00:17:11,190 --> 00:17:13,060
(They return to the farm after getting groceries.)

482
00:17:13,360 --> 00:17:15,830
(After briefly organizing the groceries)

483
00:17:17,490 --> 00:17:20,530
If you marinate this in milk, it gets rid of the gamey smell.

484
00:17:21,300 --> 00:17:22,799
- I mean the chicken.
- In milk?

485
00:17:22,800 --> 00:17:24,300
(Milk is needed for Sang Hoon's chicken curry.)

486
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:26,839
Milk also works well in curry.

487
00:17:26,840 --> 00:17:28,670
Can we get some milk?

488
00:17:30,310 --> 00:17:31,310
Sir.

489
00:17:32,380 --> 00:17:34,280
Sir, could we get some milk?

490
00:17:34,380 --> 00:17:36,049
- I'll give you some.
- Do you have milk?

491
00:17:36,050 --> 00:17:37,379
- Sang Hoon needs some.
- Milk is what we have.

492
00:17:37,380 --> 00:17:38,779
Right.

493
00:17:38,780 --> 00:17:40,719
It felt strange to buy milk somewhere else.

494
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:42,449
- We have a lot here.
- Right?

495
00:17:42,450 --> 00:17:43,589
Do you have a lot of milk?

496
00:17:43,590 --> 00:17:45,259
We have plenty of milk that you produced.

497
00:17:45,260 --> 00:17:46,040
Right.

498
00:17:46,620 --> 00:17:47,919
We have a lot of milk. I'll ask them to bring it.

499
00:17:47,920 --> 00:17:48,929
Do you have a lot of milk?

500
00:17:48,930 --> 00:17:49,990
Yes, we do.

501
00:17:50,590 --> 00:17:52,460
(The intern shows a cheesy wordplay.)

502
00:17:52,700 --> 00:17:55,169
- Are you from Chungcheong Province?
- If he pretended not to hear you,

503
00:17:55,170 --> 00:17:56,730
he doesn't get the joke.

504
00:17:57,570 --> 00:17:59,640
He just asked if you were from Chungcheong Province.

505
00:18:00,840 --> 00:18:02,309
- Shall we start?
- Yes.

506
00:18:02,310 --> 00:18:03,310
- Okay.
- Let's go.

507
00:18:04,370 --> 00:18:05,509
Sang Hoon, I'll wash these.

508
00:18:05,510 --> 00:18:07,380
They're washed carrots.

509
00:18:07,710 --> 00:18:09,580
(Washing isn't necessary.)

510
00:18:10,250 --> 00:18:11,510
Kyung Soo, what should we do?

511
00:18:12,380 --> 00:18:15,419
- What? You can help Sang Hoon.
- Sang Hoon, what should we do?

512
00:18:15,420 --> 00:18:19,659
Put some milk into that stainless steel container.

513
00:18:19,660 --> 00:18:22,289
- Cut up the chicken breast...
- And potatoes?

514
00:18:22,290 --> 00:18:24,189
and thighs...

515
00:18:24,190 --> 00:18:25,460
and let them soak in it.

516
00:18:26,360 --> 00:18:27,830
Put the chicken in here.

517
00:18:28,030 --> 00:18:29,030
Yes.

518
00:18:29,930 --> 00:18:34,040
(Director Doh's pizza will be revealed in the unaired footage.)

519
00:18:34,340 --> 00:18:36,839
This is my first time cutting chicken like this.

520
00:18:36,840 --> 00:18:38,070
- Mine too.
- Right?

521
00:18:39,180 --> 00:18:41,440
Just doing this feels somewhat satisfying.

522
00:18:41,910 --> 00:18:43,110
It feels like we're cooking.

523
00:18:44,080 --> 00:18:46,780
We feel cool from doing this.

524
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:49,119
Whenever people eat this meat,

525
00:18:49,120 --> 00:18:51,490
they'll think of us.

526
00:18:52,260 --> 00:18:53,819
How long should we marinate it?

527
00:18:53,820 --> 00:18:56,759
While I make caramelized onions,

528
00:18:56,760 --> 00:18:58,929
ten to twenty minutes will be enough.

529
00:18:58,930 --> 00:19:00,030
(Exclaiming)

530
00:19:00,730 --> 00:19:02,869
By the way, how do you make that caramel thing?

531
00:19:02,870 --> 00:19:07,169
When they turn brown, the moisture evaporates.

532
00:19:07,170 --> 00:19:08,199
With the buttery aroma,

533
00:19:08,200 --> 00:19:10,040
the onions will become sweet.

534
00:19:10,370 --> 00:19:13,239
I'll get the onions started.

535
00:19:13,240 --> 00:19:15,749
While I ask you to keep stirring them,

536
00:19:15,750 --> 00:19:18,820
- I'll try making the naan.
- You have a nice way of speaking.

537
00:19:19,320 --> 00:19:21,219
Like saying "while I ask you."

538
00:19:21,220 --> 00:19:22,590
- I see.
- What I mean is...

539
00:19:23,390 --> 00:19:25,259
It makes me feel like...

540
00:19:25,260 --> 00:19:26,489
- Respected?
- I'm part of the team.

541
00:19:26,490 --> 00:19:28,389
- Right.
- I feel like I'm really cooking.

542
00:19:28,390 --> 00:19:30,560
I'm also part of KKPP.

543
00:19:31,690 --> 00:19:35,570
(The head chef intern starts chopping onions.)

544
00:19:37,300 --> 00:19:40,299
- A little bit...
- Wait a moment.

545
00:19:40,300 --> 00:19:42,009
You cut it so evenly...

546
00:19:42,010 --> 00:19:43,539
- and neatly.
- In a clean way.

547
00:19:43,540 --> 00:19:45,070
Sang Hoon was on a cooking show.

548
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:46,779
(Former assistant to a famous chef)

549
00:19:46,780 --> 00:19:47,880
The onion...

550
00:19:48,240 --> 00:19:49,310
The onion...

551
00:19:52,550 --> 00:19:53,880
Who chops it like that?

552
00:19:55,490 --> 00:19:56,490
Sang Hoon.

553
00:19:56,690 --> 00:19:58,889
Actually,

554
00:19:58,890 --> 00:20:01,189
the grain of the onion runs this way.

555
00:20:01,190 --> 00:20:02,190
You're right.

556
00:20:02,830 --> 00:20:04,390
- Then why did you cut it like this?
- "You're right?"

557
00:20:05,160 --> 00:20:06,999
I kept changing directions,

558
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:08,800
- but I couldn't find the right one.
- Really?

559
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:11,669
Should we just do it this way today?

560
00:20:11,670 --> 00:20:12,840
With a bit of charm?

561
00:20:13,170 --> 00:20:15,810
Have you ever seen anyone cut onions like this?

562
00:20:18,110 --> 00:20:19,379
You don't know, do you?

563
00:20:19,380 --> 00:20:20,380
I don't.

564
00:20:20,381 --> 00:20:22,349
If you don't know, come over here and cut this.

565
00:20:22,350 --> 00:20:23,610
What are you doing?

566
00:20:23,910 --> 00:20:26,079
Once you cook this with butter,

567
00:20:26,080 --> 00:20:27,720
it'll taste the same anyway.

568
00:20:28,480 --> 00:20:29,550
- Are you putting it in?
- Yes.

569
00:20:30,320 --> 00:20:31,590
- Is this right?
- Yes.

570
00:20:31,890 --> 00:20:35,189
(They pour milk over neatly cut chicken.)

571
00:20:35,190 --> 00:20:37,829
Kwang Soo, we're so cool.

572
00:20:37,830 --> 00:20:40,159
I think we can start doing something with this.

573
00:20:40,160 --> 00:20:42,700
(Letting the chicken sit in the milk for a while)

574
00:20:43,230 --> 00:20:45,699
I feel like I'm doing something with the brick oven next to me.

575
00:20:45,700 --> 00:20:47,369
- Shall I prepare four potatoes?
- Okay.

576
00:20:47,370 --> 00:20:49,210
(He rinses the washed carrots.)

577
00:20:49,910 --> 00:20:51,239
Why don't we add more potatoes?

578
00:20:51,240 --> 00:20:53,040
- Five potatoes?
- CEO Hwang likes potatoes.

579
00:20:53,480 --> 00:20:54,540
That's true.

580
00:20:55,180 --> 00:20:57,350
- He eats potatoes for every meal.
- Right.

581
00:20:57,380 --> 00:20:59,279
Imagine potatoes in a curry...

582
00:20:59,280 --> 00:21:01,450
and cut them how you see fit.

583
00:21:01,820 --> 00:21:03,690
Woo Bin, don't you like chunks of potatoes in your dish?

584
00:21:04,220 --> 00:21:06,590
In a curry, they taste better as big chunks.

585
00:21:07,420 --> 00:21:09,930
Believe it or not, I've made curry a few times.

586
00:21:11,490 --> 00:21:12,700
I'm not like you.

587
00:21:13,730 --> 00:21:15,699
I made curry the day before coming to Jeju Island.

588
00:21:15,700 --> 00:21:17,030
(The competition for last place in cooking skills is fierce.)

589
00:21:17,570 --> 00:21:19,770
(CEO Lee rolls up his sleeves.)

590
00:21:22,810 --> 00:21:25,040
(Caramelizing the onions begins.)

591
00:21:25,940 --> 00:21:27,880
(The director and the auditor)

592
00:21:34,020 --> 00:21:37,920
(They cut potatoes and carrots for the curry.)

593
00:21:40,760 --> 00:21:44,160
(Meanwhile, the intern looks at the recipe for a long time.)

594
00:21:45,130 --> 00:21:47,900
(He starts making dough for the naan.)

595
00:21:48,230 --> 00:21:50,670
I have no idea how much I'm supposed to put in.

596
00:21:51,500 --> 00:21:52,500
Is this right?

597
00:21:52,770 --> 00:21:54,600
(Yeast)

598
00:21:55,100 --> 00:21:57,010
(Sugar)

599
00:21:57,910 --> 00:22:00,910
(He pours some hot water.)

600
00:22:04,280 --> 00:22:05,280
By the way...

601
00:22:06,050 --> 00:22:07,050
What?

602
00:22:07,220 --> 00:22:09,120
(Laughing)

603
00:22:10,220 --> 00:22:11,220
What is it?

604
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:13,360
It's because...

605
00:22:13,360 --> 00:22:14,360
(Glancing at it again)

606
00:22:14,890 --> 00:22:17,060
What? Why did you laugh?

607
00:22:18,090 --> 00:22:21,230
Sang Hoon, wasn't the amount indicated in the recipe?

608
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:23,030
- For the water?
- Yes.

609
00:22:23,470 --> 00:22:24,470
Right.

610
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:26,200
Did I add too much water?

611
00:22:26,740 --> 00:22:27,870
Sang Hoon.

612
00:22:28,370 --> 00:22:29,969
It's still not too late to be honest.

613
00:22:29,970 --> 00:22:31,439
Do you know how to make curry or not?

614
00:22:31,440 --> 00:22:32,509
But this is...

615
00:22:32,510 --> 00:22:33,980
(The doubts start to grow.)

616
00:22:34,140 --> 00:22:35,749
I'm making naan,

617
00:22:35,750 --> 00:22:37,309
- and it's my first time making it.
- In the recipe,

618
00:22:37,310 --> 00:22:39,579
could you check the amount...

619
00:22:39,580 --> 00:22:41,280
- All right.
- before you continue?

620
00:22:41,620 --> 00:22:42,989
Are you feeling pressured...

621
00:22:42,990 --> 00:22:44,150
because you were on a cooking show?

622
00:22:44,820 --> 00:22:47,060
I didn't do anything there except talk.

623
00:22:48,320 --> 00:22:51,159
Chef Choi Kang Rok did all the cooking.

624
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:53,799
All I did was make comments like "That looks good."

625
00:22:53,800 --> 00:22:55,330
I see.

626
00:22:56,400 --> 00:22:58,369
- Then look it up.
- Okay.

627
00:22:58,370 --> 00:22:59,769
Or call the chef.

628
00:22:59,770 --> 00:23:01,200
Do something about it.

629
00:23:01,670 --> 00:23:03,310
What are you going to do with this?

630
00:23:03,470 --> 00:23:06,080
(Yeast sugar porridge)

631
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:09,810
It requires only 3g.

632
00:23:10,710 --> 00:23:11,710
How much did you add?

633
00:23:11,711 --> 00:23:12,719
(You just found that out?)

634
00:23:12,720 --> 00:23:13,849
How much did you add?

635
00:23:13,850 --> 00:23:15,220
He poured the entire thing.

636
00:23:16,890 --> 00:23:17,890
Sang Hoon, shall I throw it away?

637
00:23:17,891 --> 00:23:19,660
No, I'll add this to the flour.

638
00:23:20,060 --> 00:23:21,890
Shall I throw it away? Would that make you feel better?

639
00:23:23,530 --> 00:23:26,400
- Is this okay to use?
- How many grams of yeast was it?

640
00:23:26,760 --> 00:23:27,760
About...

641
00:23:28,100 --> 00:23:30,470
About 15g.

642
00:23:32,470 --> 00:23:34,069
Why don't we throw it away and start again?

643
00:23:34,070 --> 00:23:36,469
We might as well since the warm water is ready.

644
00:23:36,470 --> 00:23:37,740
I'll wash it for you.

645
00:23:38,810 --> 00:23:39,810
Then...

646
00:23:40,180 --> 00:23:42,009
Can I do this instead?

647
00:23:42,010 --> 00:23:43,180
Why me?

648
00:23:43,510 --> 00:23:45,279
Why would you take over what I'm doing?

649
00:23:45,280 --> 00:23:47,220
- I...
- How low do you want me to go?

650
00:23:47,250 --> 00:23:50,089
(Things aren't working out for you.)

651
00:23:50,090 --> 00:23:53,190
I thought if I suggested something,

652
00:23:53,790 --> 00:23:56,259
Kyung Soo or others would...

653
00:23:56,260 --> 00:23:57,730
lead the rest.

654
00:23:58,360 --> 00:24:00,229
But they left me in charge of everything.

655
00:24:00,230 --> 00:24:02,870
It feels like they're telling me, "You take control!"

656
00:24:03,130 --> 00:24:05,539
That's how I feel.

657
00:24:05,540 --> 00:24:06,540
(The intern is put in charge of such a big project from the start.)

658
00:24:06,740 --> 00:24:09,210
I'll really take the scientific approach.

659
00:24:10,510 --> 00:24:14,180
I'll put 6g of instant yeast.

660
00:24:15,750 --> 00:24:17,210
(Yeast again)

661
00:24:17,380 --> 00:24:19,349
I'll add 260g.

662
00:24:19,350 --> 00:24:20,550
- Two hundred and sixty.
- Yes.

663
00:24:21,020 --> 00:24:22,220
Okay.

664
00:24:23,090 --> 00:24:25,350
- That's perfect.
- That's 260g.

665
00:24:26,060 --> 00:24:27,119
That was perfect.

666
00:24:27,120 --> 00:24:28,620
Next, 10g of sugar.

667
00:24:29,190 --> 00:24:31,490
And 400g of flour.

668
00:24:31,890 --> 00:24:33,859
Next, 6g of salt.

669
00:24:33,860 --> 00:24:35,330
(This time, the intern measures everything precisely.)

670
00:24:35,930 --> 00:24:37,469
Wait for five minutes,

671
00:24:37,470 --> 00:24:39,700
and it might start to bubble up.

672
00:24:40,970 --> 00:24:42,139
What do you mean it might?

673
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:43,240
I mean, it should.

674
00:24:43,370 --> 00:24:45,170
(He doesn't sound all that reliable.)

675
00:24:45,470 --> 00:24:47,110
What should I do, Sang Hoon?

676
00:24:47,810 --> 00:24:50,179
Throw away the milk...

677
00:24:50,180 --> 00:24:51,249
- and wash it with water.
- Wash it?

678
00:24:51,250 --> 00:24:53,219
And you could maybe grill it here.

679
00:24:53,220 --> 00:24:55,619
(His task is to wash the chicken in water and grill the surface.)

680
00:24:55,620 --> 00:24:57,719
We're in charge of a lot of important tasks.

681
00:24:57,720 --> 00:24:59,220
- I know, right?
- You need to grill it too.

682
00:24:59,690 --> 00:25:01,690
But please check it with Kyung Soo.

683
00:25:01,990 --> 00:25:03,290
- What is it?
- Should I wash this with water?

684
00:25:04,030 --> 00:25:05,260
Wash...

685
00:25:05,730 --> 00:25:07,730
Don't wash it. Use a sieve and...

686
00:25:08,870 --> 00:25:10,530
- You can use this.
- Like this?

687
00:25:12,840 --> 00:25:15,710
(He threw away only the milk and kept the chicken intact.)

688
00:25:16,210 --> 00:25:17,569
- Well...
- How is it?

689
00:25:17,570 --> 00:25:19,539
(Sang Hoon has started to make the dough for naan.)

690
00:25:19,540 --> 00:25:22,350
- It looks pretty legit.
- Right.

691
00:25:22,380 --> 00:25:24,109
Now, cook it over high heat...

692
00:25:24,110 --> 00:25:26,549
to just grill the surface.

693
00:25:26,550 --> 00:25:27,879
I'll be kneading the dough here.

694
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:28,990
Okay.

695
00:25:35,760 --> 00:25:36,790
Is this right?

696
00:25:36,930 --> 00:25:38,960
Honestly, I've never even made sujebi.

697
00:25:40,230 --> 00:25:42,030
He has never even made sujebi.

698
00:25:43,430 --> 00:25:44,930
I mean, why, from the first place...

699
00:25:46,100 --> 00:25:47,239
Tell me if I'm doing it wrong.

700
00:25:47,240 --> 00:25:48,240
It isn't too late.

701
00:25:48,241 --> 00:25:49,540
We have instant rice too.

702
00:25:50,370 --> 00:25:52,379
- We can grill the rice in the oven.
- Naan...

703
00:25:52,380 --> 00:25:53,810
Why would you grill the instant rice in the oven?

704
00:25:54,440 --> 00:25:57,450
(Their doubt became a certainty.)

705
00:25:58,780 --> 00:26:02,080
(As per the intern's instruction, he adds some oil in the pan.)

706
00:26:02,920 --> 00:26:05,390
(He starts to grill chicken.)

707
00:26:07,190 --> 00:26:10,530
(The intern kneads the dough.)

708
00:26:15,560 --> 00:26:16,670
(Glancing up)

709
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:20,340
(Glancing up again)

710
00:26:23,540 --> 00:26:26,180
(Something is going very wrong.)

711
00:26:27,540 --> 00:26:28,740
Shall I add more water?

712
00:26:29,510 --> 00:26:31,609
This is how it's supposed to be, right?

713
00:26:31,610 --> 00:26:32,680
It's supposed to be this thick, right?

714
00:26:34,020 --> 00:26:35,120
Nice.

715
00:26:35,750 --> 00:26:37,720
- Water...
- A bit more of it?

716
00:26:38,620 --> 00:26:40,319
It should unstick at least.

717
00:26:40,320 --> 00:26:41,320
I think...

718
00:26:41,820 --> 00:26:43,029
there's too much water.

719
00:26:43,030 --> 00:26:44,160
- Oh, it's the opposite?
- Yes.

720
00:26:44,190 --> 00:26:45,359
There's too much water, I see.

721
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:46,829
Shall I add more flour, then?

722
00:26:46,830 --> 00:26:48,699
- Good.
- Okay. I'll bring over the flour.

723
00:26:48,700 --> 00:26:49,700
Good.

724
00:26:50,070 --> 00:26:51,370
I took a completely opposite approach.

725
00:26:52,500 --> 00:26:54,599
(The intern is wavering. Will he be okay?)

726
00:26:54,600 --> 00:26:56,710
I think we gave him enough chances.

727
00:26:58,570 --> 00:27:01,580
Actually, this meal preparation itself...

728
00:27:01,940 --> 00:27:03,110
is Sang Hoon's farewell party.

729
00:27:05,380 --> 00:27:08,350
(He is at risk of losing his head chef position.)

730
00:27:08,450 --> 00:27:10,349
Kyung Soo, do you mind if I knead the dough?

731
00:27:10,350 --> 00:27:11,589
Sang Hoon is...

732
00:27:11,590 --> 00:27:13,989
No, Kwang Soo. Just do your onions.

733
00:27:13,990 --> 00:27:15,120
You...

734
00:27:16,890 --> 00:27:19,530
You need to attend to the onions until they turn brown.

735
00:27:20,060 --> 00:27:22,000
But he isn't making the dough right.

736
00:27:23,130 --> 00:27:25,100
(To salvage the dough,)

737
00:27:25,840 --> 00:27:28,170
(he adds some flour.)

738
00:27:29,140 --> 00:27:31,339
Right, this is how it feels.

739
00:27:31,340 --> 00:27:32,710
Yes. Now I can knead it better.

740
00:27:33,940 --> 00:27:35,639
Right. Now I get it.

741
00:27:35,640 --> 00:27:37,050
I'm more confident now.

742
00:27:38,280 --> 00:27:40,280
We shouldn't cook.

743
00:27:41,150 --> 00:27:42,595
Even with three people here,

744
00:27:43,150 --> 00:27:44,690
none of them are of help.

745
00:27:45,790 --> 00:27:47,390
I did kind of have high hopes.

746
00:27:47,620 --> 00:27:50,159
Should I put in all the meat and cook them at once?

747
00:27:50,160 --> 00:27:51,660
- I thought they'd still...
- Not you!

748
00:27:53,460 --> 00:27:54,499
I thought they'd still be able to cook somewhat.

749
00:27:54,500 --> 00:27:55,500
I'm not talking to you.

750
00:27:56,270 --> 00:27:57,270
I was wrong.

751
00:27:57,271 --> 00:27:58,299
- Kyung Soo.
- Yes?

752
00:27:58,300 --> 00:28:00,140
Should I put all the meat in and cook them at once?

753
00:28:00,340 --> 00:28:02,099
- But Sang Hoon...
- The color is changing.

754
00:28:02,100 --> 00:28:04,070
Sang Hoon has his recipe.

755
00:28:04,810 --> 00:28:05,810
And how do we cook that?

756
00:28:05,811 --> 00:28:08,239
I want to try following it...

757
00:28:08,240 --> 00:28:09,279
until the end.

758
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:10,379
(The director still has faith in the intern.)

759
00:28:10,380 --> 00:28:11,950
- Put all in?
- I want to try his food.

760
00:28:15,420 --> 00:28:17,449
(If you follow Sang Hoon's recipe, you shouldn't put all in.)

761
00:28:17,450 --> 00:28:19,220
- Enough.
- Let's just put all in.

762
00:28:20,490 --> 00:28:23,430
(Cooked meat and uncooked meat have been mixed.)

763
00:28:23,730 --> 00:28:26,060
The curry you were trying...

764
00:28:26,660 --> 00:28:28,099
to make...

765
00:28:28,100 --> 00:28:29,700
is gone now because he put in the whole thing.

766
00:28:31,300 --> 00:28:32,640
- We failed?
- Yes.

767
00:28:32,870 --> 00:28:34,899
- Because Kwang Soo put all in?
- There's a reason...

768
00:28:34,900 --> 00:28:37,010
I put Kwang Soo in charge of stir-frying onions only.

769
00:28:37,270 --> 00:28:39,639
Woo Bin was adding bit by bit.

770
00:28:39,640 --> 00:28:40,710
(Nodding)

771
00:28:41,040 --> 00:28:42,810
He's almost boiling...

772
00:28:44,810 --> 00:28:46,180
You don't cook like this even for a school lunch.

773
00:28:52,120 --> 00:28:54,960
(The CEO, who feels guilty, gets angry at him instead.)

774
00:28:56,360 --> 00:28:57,760
But there's one more...

775
00:28:59,530 --> 00:29:00,699
There's no fire.

776
00:29:00,700 --> 00:29:01,800
No fire, right?

777
00:29:02,360 --> 00:29:03,600
What are you doing?

778
00:29:04,570 --> 00:29:05,839
There's no fire underneath.

779
00:29:05,840 --> 00:29:07,339
- I mean, when we use this, - We didn't light it up yet.

780
00:29:07,340 --> 00:29:09,170
the heat might become really strong.

781
00:29:11,710 --> 00:29:13,210
Shall we ignite this, then?

782
00:29:13,640 --> 00:29:15,879
(The intern's idea has been adopted.)

783
00:29:15,880 --> 00:29:17,049
I should fan it until the fire gets stronger, right?

784
00:29:17,050 --> 00:29:19,349
Yes. I think the fire did light up.

785
00:29:19,350 --> 00:29:20,650
- It's pretty strong.
- Yes.

786
00:29:21,650 --> 00:29:22,650
By boiling it...

787
00:29:22,651 --> 00:29:23,889
(The sound of kids playing)

788
00:29:23,890 --> 00:29:25,920
We could have Ji Woo try a bite too.

789
00:29:26,060 --> 00:29:27,260
We'll make it not spicy.

790
00:29:29,390 --> 00:29:30,490
My younger sibling's sons.

791
00:29:30,890 --> 00:29:32,460
Ye Chan and Yi Chan.

792
00:29:33,560 --> 00:29:35,000
They're running around on the grass field.

793
00:29:35,130 --> 00:29:37,669
I realized now that this has...

794
00:29:37,670 --> 00:29:40,869
a lot more responsibility than cooking for myself...

795
00:29:40,870 --> 00:29:41,940
at home.

796
00:29:42,100 --> 00:29:44,069
When I cook for myself,

797
00:29:44,070 --> 00:29:46,009
I'll just go, "That wasn't nice. I'll do it this way next time."

798
00:29:46,010 --> 00:29:47,239
But thinking about...

799
00:29:47,240 --> 00:29:51,080
how I need to treat the CEO, the boss, Ye Chan, and Yi Chan...

800
00:29:51,350 --> 00:29:53,520
How can you feel the responsibility only now?

801
00:29:55,320 --> 00:29:56,889
Shouldn't you have felt it at the supermarket?

802
00:29:56,890 --> 00:29:59,960
(It's great that he realized it, but the timing is a shame.)

803
00:30:00,460 --> 00:30:03,030
(The cauldron is heated up nicely.)

804
00:30:06,100 --> 00:30:08,260
(Transfer the surface-cooked chicken into the cauldron.)

805
00:30:08,930 --> 00:30:11,330
- Shall I put in the onions too?
- Put in the onions.

806
00:30:12,600 --> 00:30:14,800
(The caramelized onions are added too.)

807
00:30:18,440 --> 00:30:21,180
(They add carrots, potatoes, and raw onions as well.)

808
00:30:23,950 --> 00:30:26,149
- It already...
- What?

809
00:30:26,150 --> 00:30:27,150
- It's turning golden-brown.
- Yes.

810
00:30:27,151 --> 00:30:29,020
- It looks delicious.
- Shall we add some pepper?

811
00:30:29,290 --> 00:30:30,350
Sounds good.

812
00:30:31,790 --> 00:30:32,860
Onions...

813
00:30:33,120 --> 00:30:35,019
He saw the onions turning brown...

814
00:30:35,020 --> 00:30:36,560
and mistook them for the chicken.

815
00:30:38,190 --> 00:30:39,200
The chicken is white.

816
00:30:43,730 --> 00:30:45,899
- With the pepper scent mixed, - Yes.

817
00:30:45,900 --> 00:30:47,440
- it has the Nepal vibe.
- Nice.

818
00:30:48,470 --> 00:30:49,509
All the water is gone.

819
00:30:49,510 --> 00:30:50,610
- Tell me when to stop.
- Okay.

820
00:30:51,170 --> 00:30:52,210
You can pour it all.

821
00:30:52,810 --> 00:30:53,840
Stop.

822
00:30:57,580 --> 00:31:00,679
(Pour water and curry onto the well-cooked ingredients.)

823
00:31:00,680 --> 00:31:01,680
Nice.

824
00:31:02,650 --> 00:31:04,050
This is really thick.

825
00:31:05,420 --> 00:31:09,990
(He adds the tomato paste, the kick to this curry.)

826
00:31:10,490 --> 00:31:11,560
It's getting thicker.

827
00:31:12,390 --> 00:31:15,030
(While the curry is getting ready)

828
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:17,000
Nobody may acknowledge it,

829
00:31:17,001 --> 00:31:19,000
but you're quietly doing your job away from the spotlight.

830
00:31:19,600 --> 00:31:20,600
I have nothing else to do.

831
00:31:22,140 --> 00:31:23,210
This is the only thing I can do.

832
00:31:23,770 --> 00:31:26,180
(The auditor does the donkey work.)

833
00:31:28,210 --> 00:31:30,610
(Tasting)

834
00:31:31,350 --> 00:31:32,509
(Kwang Soo is amazed.)

835
00:31:32,510 --> 00:31:33,850
- It's so good.
- Really?

836
00:31:34,020 --> 00:31:35,020
It's so good.

837
00:31:36,020 --> 00:31:37,689
It tastes better because of the chicken broth.

838
00:31:37,690 --> 00:31:39,190
- There's a strong chicken smell.
- Right?

839
00:31:39,820 --> 00:31:40,859
You mean...

840
00:31:40,860 --> 00:31:42,259
(It doesn't sound right when you say "chicken smell.")

841
00:31:42,260 --> 00:31:43,829
I mean, it's a good thing. Chicken flavor...

842
00:31:43,830 --> 00:31:45,189
Say chicken broth.

843
00:31:45,190 --> 00:31:46,560
Mr. Lal would love it.

844
00:31:47,360 --> 00:31:49,530
(They each taste the curry.)

845
00:31:49,870 --> 00:31:51,000
- It's good, right?
- Yes.

846
00:31:52,100 --> 00:31:53,369
It already tastes good.

847
00:31:53,370 --> 00:31:55,369
- Is it good?
- Yes, it's already good.

848
00:31:55,370 --> 00:31:56,670
(The curry is more or less done.)

849
00:31:57,140 --> 00:31:58,970
The naan is the problem.

850
00:32:00,240 --> 00:32:02,950
(Taking out the dough which was rested for 30 minutes)

851
00:32:03,980 --> 00:32:07,380
(Make it flat using the rolling pin.)

852
00:32:10,550 --> 00:32:11,620
Let's test it.

853
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:15,620
(Will it cook well in the oven?)

854
00:32:16,290 --> 00:32:17,990
(The spectators gather round.)

855
00:32:18,690 --> 00:32:20,999
My gosh!

856
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:22,230
I think it's baking!

857
00:32:22,800 --> 00:32:24,470
- What? No, we just put it in.
- Really?

858
00:32:25,100 --> 00:32:26,199
We put it in just a second ago.

859
00:32:26,200 --> 00:32:28,339
It looks like it's bubbling up.

860
00:32:28,340 --> 00:32:29,770
- No, not yet.
- No?

861
00:32:29,940 --> 00:32:32,170
(The naan dough is exposed to the heat of the oven.)

862
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:35,279
I think it'll work.

863
00:32:35,280 --> 00:32:37,210
- I think it's cooked properly.
- Really?

864
00:32:37,350 --> 00:32:38,709
Look. Like a tortilla...

865
00:32:38,710 --> 00:32:40,750
It looks like what they sell at restaurants.

866
00:32:41,580 --> 00:32:43,720
It needs to be baked longer,

867
00:32:44,350 --> 00:32:45,820
but it would work.

868
00:32:47,420 --> 00:32:48,489
It's still dough.

869
00:32:48,490 --> 00:32:50,229
- Let's cook it longer.
- It looks like naan.

870
00:32:50,230 --> 00:32:51,690
(They see hope.)

871
00:32:52,030 --> 00:32:54,059
Shall I roll it out bigger?

872
00:32:54,060 --> 00:32:55,700
- Since it's working?
- Yes, you can work on the dough.

873
00:32:56,300 --> 00:32:57,999
(They start to produce the naan.)

874
00:32:58,000 --> 00:32:59,800
Use a lot of dusting flour.

875
00:33:00,270 --> 00:33:03,040
Sang Hoon, it was a great idea to bake naan.

876
00:33:04,810 --> 00:33:06,040
I really hope it tastes good.

877
00:33:06,780 --> 00:33:07,840
I think it will be.

878
00:33:08,380 --> 00:33:10,379
- That...
- Dip it in curry,

879
00:33:10,380 --> 00:33:12,010
- and it tastes amazing.
- Right.

880
00:33:19,360 --> 00:33:20,490
It's done, right?

881
00:33:20,960 --> 00:33:22,019
Yes.

882
00:33:22,020 --> 00:33:23,090
It feels like...

883
00:33:24,190 --> 00:33:26,030
I'm doing something very important.

884
00:33:27,060 --> 00:33:28,130
- Woo Bin.
- Yes?

885
00:33:28,730 --> 00:33:30,130
You're eliminated.

886
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:32,900
- Why?
- It's too thick here.

887
00:33:33,540 --> 00:33:35,239
Thick parts are tasty.

888
00:33:35,240 --> 00:33:36,269
What about mine?

889
00:33:36,270 --> 00:33:37,669
- This is a pass, right?
- This is...

890
00:33:37,670 --> 00:33:39,010
- This is a pass.
- Right?

891
00:33:39,840 --> 00:33:40,879
(Unhappy)

892
00:33:40,880 --> 00:33:43,109
The fire is weak, so it won't be baked.

893
00:33:43,110 --> 00:33:44,610
- I mean the thick parts.
- Okay.

894
00:33:45,510 --> 00:33:47,280
I should put the whole thing in.

895
00:33:50,090 --> 00:33:53,060
(The naan is placed on a tray and put into the oven.)

896
00:33:53,790 --> 00:33:56,020
Sang Hoon, don't use oil...

897
00:33:57,430 --> 00:33:59,330
and bake it on this heat.

898
00:33:59,960 --> 00:34:01,260
Let's try one.

899
00:34:01,460 --> 00:34:03,169
This might taste better.

900
00:34:03,170 --> 00:34:04,929
Then I'll try one without butter...

901
00:34:04,930 --> 00:34:06,199
and one with butter.

902
00:34:06,200 --> 00:34:07,200
Sounds amazing.

903
00:34:08,940 --> 00:34:11,610
(The director opens the oven.)

904
00:34:19,050 --> 00:34:20,080
This...

905
00:34:21,150 --> 00:34:22,649
- Like this.
- Nice.

906
00:34:22,650 --> 00:34:24,750
- Gosh, what's this?
- Nice.

907
00:34:25,190 --> 00:34:26,560
This is just like what they sell.

908
00:34:28,590 --> 00:34:31,089
(The oven naan is a success!)

909
00:34:31,090 --> 00:34:32,590
We can continue to bake with the oven.

910
00:34:33,330 --> 00:34:34,700
Let's go two-track.

911
00:34:34,800 --> 00:34:36,499
- Sure.
- All we need to do now...

912
00:34:36,500 --> 00:34:37,500
- is to keep it going.
- In that case,

913
00:34:37,501 --> 00:34:38,529
why don't you make the one with butter?

914
00:34:38,530 --> 00:34:40,070
- Okay. My goodness.
- Since he doesn't use butter.

915
00:34:40,440 --> 00:34:42,170
- You're really...
- Hey.

916
00:34:42,270 --> 00:34:43,270
- You're so...
- How is it?

917
00:34:43,271 --> 00:34:44,639
The dignity of the CEO.

918
00:34:44,640 --> 00:34:46,509
Why don't we taste both in one meal?

919
00:34:46,510 --> 00:34:48,140
You're insane.

920
00:34:48,880 --> 00:34:50,880
- Yi Chan can have the buttered one.
- Yes.

921
00:34:50,980 --> 00:34:52,680
The CEO can have the plain, original flavor.

922
00:34:54,120 --> 00:34:55,949
And the seniors can feel the taste of their traditional food...

923
00:34:55,950 --> 00:34:56,950
That's right.

924
00:34:56,950 --> 00:34:57,950
and our own unique style...

925
00:34:57,951 --> 00:34:59,249
- That's right.
- at the same time.

926
00:34:59,250 --> 00:35:00,359
Killing 2 birds with 1 stone.

927
00:35:00,360 --> 00:35:01,889
Let's make Mr. Kkalloo and Mr. Lal cry today.

928
00:35:01,890 --> 00:35:02,890
Yes.

929
00:35:02,891 --> 00:35:04,960
(Thanks to the naan being a success, their teamwork has also improved.)

930
00:35:05,160 --> 00:35:06,230
- Sang Hoon.
- Yes?

931
00:35:06,900 --> 00:35:07,900
Can you check this?

932
00:35:08,630 --> 00:35:11,230
I'm not trying to show off or anything.

933
00:35:12,370 --> 00:35:13,639
See if I'm doing this smartly.

934
00:35:13,640 --> 00:35:14,640
Okay.

935
00:35:15,500 --> 00:35:16,509
How's this?

936
00:35:16,510 --> 00:35:17,939
(Rolling out two at once)

937
00:35:17,940 --> 00:35:19,940
You don't get this kind...

938
00:35:20,640 --> 00:35:22,010
of wisdom of life easily.

939
00:35:23,710 --> 00:35:24,710
I don't know. I'm just...

940
00:35:24,711 --> 00:35:26,009
Have you done this before?

941
00:35:26,010 --> 00:35:27,179
- This...
- No, it's my first time doing it.

942
00:35:27,180 --> 00:35:28,719
Really? And yet you can do this?

943
00:35:28,720 --> 00:35:30,049
I've never even worked part-time at a restaurant.

944
00:35:30,050 --> 00:35:31,050
This is crazy.

945
00:35:31,050 --> 00:35:32,050
(The intern became the parrot to the captain.)

946
00:35:32,450 --> 00:35:34,360
- But somehow, I thought...
- What?

947
00:35:35,390 --> 00:35:36,390
Why does everyone...

948
00:35:36,960 --> 00:35:38,129
- roll out 1 at a time?
- Roll out 1 at a time?

949
00:35:38,130 --> 00:35:39,130
Seriously.

950
00:35:39,130 --> 00:35:40,130
If you do this like this,

951
00:35:42,260 --> 00:35:44,170
you can cut down the time to half.

952
00:35:44,670 --> 00:35:45,870
I had this thought.

953
00:35:46,300 --> 00:35:49,240
(Meanwhile, the director tastes the curry.)

954
00:35:50,140 --> 00:35:52,979
(He wraps the well-cooked chicken with naan.)

955
00:35:52,980 --> 00:35:54,279
I had this thought.

956
00:35:54,280 --> 00:35:56,350
(He lets the CEO taste it first.)

957
00:35:57,180 --> 00:35:59,350
- My gosh.
- You're doing two at once.

958
00:36:00,050 --> 00:36:01,749
- This is...
- Is it good?

959
00:36:01,750 --> 00:36:02,889
We should sell it right now.

960
00:36:02,890 --> 00:36:03,890
It worked?

961
00:36:04,690 --> 00:36:05,690
I'm serious.

962
00:36:05,691 --> 00:36:07,560
Is the naan good? Really?

963
00:36:07,790 --> 00:36:09,319
I'm glad we cooked a lot of chicken.

964
00:36:09,320 --> 00:36:10,960
(The auditor, who worked hard doing the dishes, tastes it too.)

965
00:36:11,030 --> 00:36:13,060
It tastes amazing wrapped in naan.

966
00:36:14,400 --> 00:36:15,700
- Goodness.
- It's good, right?

967
00:36:16,630 --> 00:36:17,630
Isn't it so good?

968
00:36:17,700 --> 00:36:19,570
This tastes exactly like what they sell at restaurants.

969
00:36:19,900 --> 00:36:22,669
I honestly didn't expect it to taste this good.

970
00:36:22,670 --> 00:36:23,670
My gosh.

971
00:36:23,810 --> 00:36:26,880
All of this started from the Jocheon supermarket.

972
00:36:26,980 --> 00:36:28,279
(The birthplace of the innovative taste,)

973
00:36:28,280 --> 00:36:29,580
(the Jocheon supermarket)

974
00:36:29,780 --> 00:36:30,809
- Sang Hoon.
- If Mr. Kkalloo asks...

975
00:36:30,810 --> 00:36:31,810
where we bought this from...

976
00:36:33,580 --> 00:36:35,080
(Impressed)

977
00:36:36,050 --> 00:36:37,620
(It deserves an applause.)

978
00:36:39,660 --> 00:36:41,489
(He scoops up the curry with care.)

979
00:36:41,490 --> 00:36:42,520
This.

980
00:36:45,090 --> 00:36:46,660
It's really like a dessert.

981
00:36:47,660 --> 00:36:49,670
(He prepares the dessert, the grilled rice cake.)

982
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:54,170
How many of us are there?

983
00:36:55,140 --> 00:36:57,110
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven.

984
00:36:57,870 --> 00:36:59,239
Sang Hoon, we need two more.

985
00:36:59,240 --> 00:37:00,240
Coming.

986
00:37:00,440 --> 00:37:02,310
Gosh, when did you come?

987
00:37:02,810 --> 00:37:03,880
Do you want to try one?

988
00:37:04,210 --> 00:37:05,280
Yes.

989
00:37:05,380 --> 00:37:07,680
- I washed my hands.
- Okay.

990
00:37:09,076 --> 00:37:09,843
Try it.

991
00:37:10,950 --> 00:37:12,219
- How is it?
- It's good.

992
00:37:12,220 --> 00:37:13,320
It's good, right?

993
00:37:14,390 --> 00:37:15,719
(Expressing how good the rice cake is with her whole body)

994
00:37:15,720 --> 00:37:16,890
It's very good, right?

995
00:37:18,660 --> 00:37:20,659
(They're almost done with setting the table.)

996
00:37:20,660 --> 00:37:22,860
(Woo Bin's hands are full of something.)

997
00:37:23,300 --> 00:37:24,530
Are you decorating the table with flowers even in your house?

998
00:37:24,630 --> 00:37:25,630
Come on.

999
00:37:25,631 --> 00:37:26,640
(Flowers?)

1000
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:28,600
You must always mind your manners...

1001
00:37:29,040 --> 00:37:30,440
to greet the guests.

1002
00:37:31,010 --> 00:37:34,810
(Curry and naan)

1003
00:37:35,380 --> 00:37:37,249
(Grilled rice cake)

1004
00:37:37,250 --> 00:37:39,579
(Gratitude and manners added too)

1005
00:37:39,580 --> 00:37:41,280
Camellia flowers which had fallen to the ground.

1006
00:37:42,550 --> 00:37:44,520
Nice. The table became brighter.

1007
00:37:44,620 --> 00:37:48,990
(A romantic outdoor meal is ready.)

1008
00:37:50,130 --> 00:37:53,059
(The guests come over one after another.)

1009
00:37:53,060 --> 00:37:54,130
Please have a seat, sir.

1010
00:37:55,560 --> 00:37:57,170
- Have a seat.
- Okay.

1011
00:37:58,070 --> 00:37:59,599
- Are you sitting here?
- Come here.

1012
00:37:59,600 --> 00:38:00,970
- I'll sit here.
- Okay.

1013
00:38:01,070 --> 00:38:03,039
This is just curry.

1014
00:38:03,040 --> 00:38:06,240
- Yes.
- I heard Mr. Lal liked chicken.

1015
00:38:06,380 --> 00:38:07,910
So we cooked a lot of chicken.

1016
00:38:08,240 --> 00:38:09,779
- We cooked a lot of chicken.
- Thank you.

1017
00:38:09,780 --> 00:38:11,349
And I heard the CEO and his wife...

1018
00:38:11,350 --> 00:38:13,980
- liked potatoes, so potatoes too...
- Yes.

1019
00:38:14,480 --> 00:38:16,149
- Until the end...
- Please have a seat.

1020
00:38:16,150 --> 00:38:18,390
- Okay.
- Take as much as you can eat.

1021
00:38:18,490 --> 00:38:20,419
- Sir, let me serve you first.
- Okay.

1022
00:38:20,420 --> 00:38:21,620
Thank you.

1023
00:38:22,490 --> 00:38:23,729
Don't mix the whole thing at once.

1024
00:38:23,730 --> 00:38:25,690
Mix it bit by bit. Salty...

1025
00:38:25,790 --> 00:38:26,929
- Okay.
- It could be salty.

1026
00:38:26,930 --> 00:38:28,659
- It's okay.
- Please come.

1027
00:38:28,660 --> 00:38:29,669
No.

1028
00:38:29,670 --> 00:38:30,670
Inside here...

1029
00:38:31,100 --> 00:38:33,170
Ye Chan and Yi Chan, can you eat spicy food?

1030
00:38:33,500 --> 00:38:35,070
- The taste is familiar to me.
- Curry.

1031
00:38:35,640 --> 00:38:36,869
- Thank you for the food.
- Thank you.

1032
00:38:36,870 --> 00:38:38,309
- Enjoy your meal.
- Enjoy.

1033
00:38:38,310 --> 00:38:39,310
Is it good?

1034
00:38:39,311 --> 00:38:40,739
(They finally start eating.)

1035
00:38:40,740 --> 00:38:42,140
- Does the naan taste good?
- Yes.

1036
00:38:44,180 --> 00:38:46,850
(They taste the curry first.)

1037
00:38:48,150 --> 00:38:49,180
My gosh.

1038
00:38:52,050 --> 00:38:54,320
Mr. Lal, you like it because there's a lot of chicken, right?

1039
00:38:55,390 --> 00:38:57,330
We cooked this ourselves.

1040
00:38:57,960 --> 00:38:59,360
You take spicy food very well.

1041
00:38:59,730 --> 00:39:01,500
(Glancing)

1042
00:39:01,700 --> 00:39:03,830
(He keeps checking others' reactions.)

1043
00:39:04,700 --> 00:39:07,940
(Mr. Kkalloo next to him...)

1044
00:39:08,540 --> 00:39:10,910
(folds the naan nicely.)

1045
00:39:12,470 --> 00:39:16,010
(He puts it into his mouth at once.)

1046
00:39:19,450 --> 00:39:22,279
(The CEO was eating quietly.)

1047
00:39:22,280 --> 00:39:24,019
- Yes.
- We have this too.

1048
00:39:24,020 --> 00:39:25,689
(He finally says his first sentence.)

1049
00:39:25,690 --> 00:39:27,690
This is totally Nepali cuisine.

1050
00:39:27,790 --> 00:39:28,790
- Is it?
- Yes.

1051
00:39:28,791 --> 00:39:29,959
It tastes like what I eat at home.

1052
00:39:29,960 --> 00:39:31,290
Really?

1053
00:39:31,860 --> 00:39:33,260
It tastes like what I eat at home.

1054
00:39:33,430 --> 00:39:34,430
(He lightens up.)

1055
00:39:34,431 --> 00:39:35,859
I mean it.

1056
00:39:35,860 --> 00:39:38,229
The spices totally taste Nepalese.

1057
00:39:38,230 --> 00:39:39,530
(Thankfully, his food has satisfied the guests.)

1058
00:39:39,870 --> 00:39:40,939
Is it similar to Nepalese food?

1059
00:39:40,940 --> 00:39:41,969
It's similar.

1060
00:39:41,970 --> 00:39:43,169
- It's similar.
- The spicy one...

1061
00:39:43,170 --> 00:39:46,370
The ingredients are different, but the flavor is very similar.

1062
00:39:46,980 --> 00:39:48,580
It reminds me of Nepal.

1063
00:39:48,680 --> 00:39:50,380
(Laughing)

1064
00:39:50,750 --> 00:39:52,349
(Everyone is satisfied with the taste.)

1065
00:39:52,350 --> 00:39:53,820
- I feel rewarded.
- Me too.

1066
00:39:54,580 --> 00:39:55,580
Is it good?

1067
00:39:56,180 --> 00:39:57,220
Is the naan good?

1068
00:39:58,190 --> 00:40:00,660
You know you've really succeeded when kids like your food.

1069
00:40:00,820 --> 00:40:02,189
He finished the whole thing.

1070
00:40:02,190 --> 00:40:03,190
(The kids like the savory naan.)

1071
00:40:04,230 --> 00:40:09,030
(The trainees, who've cooked the meal, taste the food too.)

1072
00:40:09,330 --> 00:40:10,669
Is it because we boiled it for a long time?

1073
00:40:10,670 --> 00:40:11,999
The chicken is very tender.

1074
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,000
- It is.
- Yes.

1075
00:40:13,640 --> 00:40:16,569
But we didn't add any extra spices.

1076
00:40:16,570 --> 00:40:18,370
- No.
- So how did it end up like this?

1077
00:40:18,510 --> 00:40:19,510
I know, right?

1078
00:40:20,280 --> 00:40:21,280
Is it good?

1079
00:40:21,740 --> 00:40:23,649
- He's eating so well.
- Is it good?

1080
00:40:23,650 --> 00:40:25,850
(Sang Hoon enjoys his meal with a much lighter heart.)

1081
00:40:26,310 --> 00:40:29,620
Mr. Lal and Mr. Kkalloo. There's more curry.

1082
00:40:30,320 --> 00:40:31,690
- Would you like more?
- You're full?

1083
00:40:32,420 --> 00:40:34,020
Would you like a bit more?

1084
00:40:34,390 --> 00:40:35,519
Then I'll have a bit more.

1085
00:40:35,520 --> 00:40:36,559
- It's so good.
- Okay.

1086
00:40:36,560 --> 00:40:38,260
(Yes, please.)

1087
00:40:39,390 --> 00:40:42,700
(While he fills up the second bowl...)

1088
00:40:43,530 --> 00:40:45,030
(He checks something.)

1089
00:40:45,400 --> 00:40:46,900
Do you know what's funny?

1090
00:40:48,140 --> 00:40:50,010
Mr. Lal doesn't like potatoes.

1091
00:40:50,510 --> 00:40:51,510
(Checking)

1092
00:40:51,511 --> 00:40:52,569
(Laughing)

1093
00:40:52,570 --> 00:40:55,440
And Mr. Kkalloo doesn't like carrots.

1094
00:40:56,580 --> 00:40:58,210
- Really?
- They...

1095
00:40:58,380 --> 00:41:00,180
He has this much potatoes left,

1096
00:41:00,480 --> 00:41:02,350
- and he has this much carrots left.
- Why won't you eat them?

1097
00:41:03,520 --> 00:41:05,449
You haven't eaten any potatoes and carrots.

1098
00:41:05,450 --> 00:41:06,450
(At the appearance of the food police,)

1099
00:41:06,920 --> 00:41:07,920
(he quickly destroys the evidence.)

1100
00:41:07,920 --> 00:41:08,920
You don't like carrots?

1101
00:41:09,220 --> 00:41:11,290
I do eat them, but...

1102
00:41:11,830 --> 00:41:12,830
You don't like potatoes?

1103
00:41:12,831 --> 00:41:14,760
I really like them.

1104
00:41:15,160 --> 00:41:17,100
I eat them in soup too.

1105
00:41:17,400 --> 00:41:19,270
(For some reason, he continued to explain himself.)

1106
00:41:19,670 --> 00:41:22,039
This is warm.

1107
00:41:22,040 --> 00:41:23,609
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

1108
00:41:23,610 --> 00:41:24,640
Drink water.

1109
00:41:25,270 --> 00:41:26,309
Would you like more, sir?

1110
00:41:26,310 --> 00:41:28,309
- I'll help myself, thanks.
- Okay.

1111
00:41:28,310 --> 00:41:29,680
- There's rice too.
- Okay.

1112
00:41:33,180 --> 00:41:34,919
(The joyful meal continues.)

1113
00:41:34,920 --> 00:41:36,180
Why? Is it spicy?

1114
00:41:40,590 --> 00:41:42,720
(She eats the grilled rice cake too.)

1115
00:41:43,690 --> 00:41:46,860
(Watching her eat makes them feel rewarded.)

1116
00:41:47,500 --> 00:41:50,899
We should be treating you.

1117
00:41:50,900 --> 00:41:52,200
Don't say that.

1118
00:41:52,300 --> 00:41:53,900
We've received a lot more.

1119
00:41:54,900 --> 00:41:57,309
We appreciate the sentiment. Thank you.

1120
00:41:57,310 --> 00:42:00,180
(A meal with heartwarming exchange)

1121
00:42:00,780 --> 00:42:01,780
You want to leave now?

1122
00:42:01,781 --> 00:42:02,979
Do you want to go to Mom?

1123
00:42:02,980 --> 00:42:04,049
Thank them for the meal first.

1124
00:42:04,050 --> 00:42:05,280
Thank you for the food.

1125
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:08,120
- No problem.
- No problem.

1126
00:42:08,980 --> 00:42:11,349
Her bottom is soiled. Even that is cute.

1127
00:42:11,350 --> 00:42:12,950
(The kids leave after finishing their food.)

1128
00:42:13,590 --> 00:42:15,289
Look at how Ji Woo smiles as she runs to you.

1129
00:42:15,290 --> 00:42:17,030
- So cute.
- I agree.

1130
00:42:17,690 --> 00:42:19,089
Ji Woo, where have you been?

1131
00:42:19,090 --> 00:42:20,959
(They thought Ji Woo had left, but she came back.)

1132
00:42:20,960 --> 00:42:22,300
Where have you been?

1133
00:42:22,400 --> 00:42:24,069
Who likes this?

1134
00:42:24,070 --> 00:42:25,570
- Uncle here!
- Me.

1135
00:42:25,670 --> 00:42:27,100
- Uncle here!
- Me.

1136
00:42:27,200 --> 00:42:29,370
(Cheering loudly)

1137
00:42:30,010 --> 00:42:31,309
(She leaves after handing him an unknown drawing.)

1138
00:42:31,310 --> 00:42:32,470
Who is this?

1139
00:42:33,070 --> 00:42:34,780
- You!
- It's me?

1140
00:42:35,480 --> 00:42:38,580
(Ji Woo wanted to gift him the drawing of the uncle.)

1141
00:42:39,280 --> 00:42:41,180
- Thank you, Ji Woo.
- You're welcome.

1142
00:42:41,920 --> 00:42:43,690
(After that, Ji Woo got on a roll.)

1143
00:42:43,850 --> 00:42:44,890
There's more?

1144
00:42:45,220 --> 00:42:46,220
Who likes this?

1145
00:42:46,221 --> 00:42:47,889
- Me!
- Me!

1146
00:42:47,890 --> 00:42:49,989
Me!

1147
00:42:49,990 --> 00:42:51,260
- Me!
- Me!

1148
00:42:51,376 --> 00:42:52,260
Me!

1149
00:42:52,660 --> 00:42:54,760
(Woo Bin is chosen.)

1150
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:57,029
She drew Woo Bin.

1151
00:42:57,030 --> 00:42:59,200
She did. The hair is short.

1152
00:43:00,940 --> 00:43:03,370
(To Sang Hoon, who's been waiting)

1153
00:43:03,870 --> 00:43:06,339
(Cheering excitedly)

1154
00:43:06,340 --> 00:43:07,340
Let me see.

1155
00:43:08,140 --> 00:43:09,580
She drew you.

1156
00:43:10,710 --> 00:43:12,510
Printing out a photo is cheating, Ji Woo!

1157
00:43:13,520 --> 00:43:14,820
- Yi Chan, me too.
- A photo...

1158
00:43:15,550 --> 00:43:17,649
Kwang Soo, she drew us all...

1159
00:43:17,650 --> 00:43:18,650
differently.

1160
00:43:18,651 --> 00:43:20,159
You're right.

1161
00:43:20,160 --> 00:43:22,120
Mine has an overwhelmingly big head.

1162
00:43:24,460 --> 00:43:25,460
This is really...

1163
00:43:25,630 --> 00:43:27,859
She's talented.

1164
00:43:27,860 --> 00:43:29,329
(Put together, you can clearly tell what the artist had intended.)

1165
00:43:29,330 --> 00:43:30,629
Sang Hoon's is practically a photo.

1166
00:43:30,630 --> 00:43:31,769
I like it.

1167
00:43:31,770 --> 00:43:34,170
I thought she was running with your ID photo.

1168
00:43:35,800 --> 00:43:36,909
This is so funny.

1169
00:43:36,910 --> 00:43:37,910
(With that, they finish the meal.)

1170
00:43:37,911 --> 00:43:39,569
I wonder what she drew.

1171
00:43:39,570 --> 00:43:40,780
(After the feast,)

1172
00:43:42,340 --> 00:43:43,849
(they've come for the last task of the training.)

1173
00:43:43,850 --> 00:43:46,550
Gogo.

1174
00:43:46,820 --> 00:43:48,549
- They're going out, right?
- Yes.

1175
00:43:48,550 --> 00:43:49,719
- Their first time?
- Isn't it their first time?

1176
00:43:49,720 --> 00:43:50,720
- Yes.
- Gosh.

1177
00:43:50,721 --> 00:43:52,089
Their first outing.

1178
00:43:52,090 --> 00:43:54,660
(Gogo and Farmfarm's first-ever outing)

1179
00:43:55,660 --> 00:43:57,029
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

1180
00:43:57,030 --> 00:43:58,359
- Oh, my.
- It's running.

1181
00:43:58,360 --> 00:43:59,589
- Let's go.
- Someone's excited.

1182
00:43:59,590 --> 00:44:01,599
Isn't it its first time walking down here?

1183
00:44:01,600 --> 00:44:02,760
(Everyone is excited.)

1184
00:44:03,330 --> 00:44:04,330
This way.

1185
00:44:04,331 --> 00:44:06,529
- Let's go.
- Do you want to go this way?

1186
00:44:06,530 --> 00:44:08,170
- Come here, Farmfarm.
- Let's go.

1187
00:44:08,840 --> 00:44:10,169
- This way.
- Good luck.

1188
00:44:10,170 --> 00:44:12,309
Come. Walk this way out.

1189
00:44:12,310 --> 00:44:15,939
(Farmfarm walks outside first.)

1190
00:44:15,940 --> 00:44:16,950
This way.

1191
00:44:17,850 --> 00:44:18,850
Farmfarm.

1192
00:44:18,910 --> 00:44:20,450
Let's go. It's not that way. Come this way.

1193
00:44:20,750 --> 00:44:22,620
This way.

1194
00:44:23,450 --> 00:44:24,450
Let's go.

1195
00:44:24,451 --> 00:44:26,120
(The outside is new to Farmfarm.)

1196
00:44:26,290 --> 00:44:27,689
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

1197
00:44:27,690 --> 00:44:28,989
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

1198
00:44:28,990 --> 00:44:29,990
It's scared.

1199
00:44:29,991 --> 00:44:31,690
- Let's go.
- Let's go. It's holding out.

1200
00:44:33,060 --> 00:44:34,060
Gogo.

1201
00:44:34,061 --> 00:44:35,199
(Hesitating about stepping forward)

1202
00:44:35,200 --> 00:44:36,200
Farmfarm.

1203
00:44:36,660 --> 00:44:37,669
The first outing...

1204
00:44:37,670 --> 00:44:39,029
must've startled them.

1205
00:44:39,030 --> 00:44:40,739
- This way.
- Come this way.

1206
00:44:40,740 --> 00:44:42,469
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

1207
00:44:42,470 --> 00:44:45,440
(The trainees help the calves take more steps outside.)

1208
00:44:46,370 --> 00:44:47,539
It's... Look!

1209
00:44:47,540 --> 00:44:48,540
Let's go.

1210
00:44:50,750 --> 00:44:52,609
(Stepping on the grass for the first time)

1211
00:44:52,610 --> 00:44:54,149
Isn't it the first time ever to jump around?

1212
00:44:54,150 --> 00:44:55,719
Exactly.

1213
00:44:55,720 --> 00:44:56,820
Goodness.

1214
00:44:56,920 --> 00:44:58,189
It couldn't even stand up properly...

1215
00:44:58,190 --> 00:44:59,419
- a couple of days ago.
- I know, right?

1216
00:44:59,420 --> 00:45:00,420
(It's the moment they feel proud.)

1217
00:45:00,860 --> 00:45:02,059
Let's go.

1218
00:45:02,060 --> 00:45:03,559
(Their first outing with the trainees)

1219
00:45:03,560 --> 00:45:05,990
- Nice.
- Oh, my.

1220
00:45:06,730 --> 00:45:08,259
Jump!

1221
00:45:08,260 --> 00:45:09,699
Goodness.

1222
00:45:09,700 --> 00:45:12,200
- It must be happy.
- Yes, it must be happy.

1223
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:14,269
Gogo.

1224
00:45:14,270 --> 00:45:15,499
(Successfully completed the last task)

1225
00:45:15,500 --> 00:45:17,670
(How was the first training?)

1226
00:45:17,740 --> 00:45:20,439
It was a new kind of experience.

1227
00:45:20,440 --> 00:45:22,610
A new experience mixed with novel feelings.

1228
00:45:22,980 --> 00:45:26,550
This training was full of those.

1229
00:45:28,280 --> 00:45:29,550
Coming up to me...

1230
00:45:30,850 --> 00:45:32,789
- and sticking close to me is...
- I know.

1231
00:45:32,790 --> 00:45:34,489
Do cows actually do this?

1232
00:45:34,490 --> 00:45:36,060
Where else could we experience this?

1233
00:45:39,430 --> 00:45:42,830
(While bidding each other a passionate farewell)

1234
00:45:43,730 --> 00:45:45,629
I wondered what it'd be like, but as expected,

1235
00:45:45,630 --> 00:45:46,870
cows are angels.

1236
00:45:47,370 --> 00:45:50,210
Cows are such kind animals.

1237
00:45:50,710 --> 00:45:52,740
Everything was new to me.

1238
00:45:53,240 --> 00:45:55,340
Some tasks were tough.

1239
00:45:55,610 --> 00:45:56,810
But I found...

1240
00:45:57,250 --> 00:45:59,280
tricks along the way.

1241
00:45:59,550 --> 00:46:01,250
It was fun.

1242
00:46:01,550 --> 00:46:02,550
Personally, that is.

1243
00:46:02,720 --> 00:46:05,020
I simply thought it'd be full of labor.

1244
00:46:05,920 --> 00:46:07,390
It's strange.

1245
00:46:07,560 --> 00:46:09,720
I've become attached to them in just three days.

1246
00:46:10,060 --> 00:46:12,189
(Some got attached.)

1247
00:46:12,190 --> 00:46:13,190
I have.

1248
00:46:13,460 --> 00:46:14,659
Since we worked together...

1249
00:46:14,660 --> 00:46:16,929
and I contributed as much,

1250
00:46:16,930 --> 00:46:18,899
I couldn't help but think...

1251
00:46:18,900 --> 00:46:21,169
I became a team member with them.

1252
00:46:21,170 --> 00:46:22,239
Despite being an intern.

1253
00:46:22,240 --> 00:46:24,440
(Some felt proud to become a teammate during the 3 days.)

1254
00:46:25,170 --> 00:46:27,810
(It's time to go home now.)

1255
00:46:27,880 --> 00:46:30,550
The CEO, our boss,

1256
00:46:31,750 --> 00:46:33,520
and the seniors were all so kind.

1257
00:46:34,380 --> 00:46:36,319
Now that three days have passed,

1258
00:46:36,320 --> 00:46:37,520
I feel sad.

1259
00:46:38,820 --> 00:46:41,160
Such an experience is rare in people's lives.

1260
00:46:42,160 --> 00:46:43,460
That made it fun.

1261
00:46:43,790 --> 00:46:45,560
Laughing with a group of people.

1262
00:46:48,530 --> 00:46:50,330
I grew fond of them.

1263
00:46:51,270 --> 00:46:53,940
Laughing and more.

1264
00:46:55,370 --> 00:46:56,540
It's sad.

1265
00:46:59,370 --> 00:47:03,440
(Check out the rest of the dairy farm story in the last episode!)

1266
00:47:04,080 --> 00:47:06,110
What if you were asked to become an official intern?

1267
00:47:06,920 --> 00:47:09,519
I see. So what if I'm asked to become an official intern,

1268
00:47:09,520 --> 00:47:11,490
not a full-time worker?

1269
00:47:12,050 --> 00:47:14,689
I'm not even sure if I'd accept a full-time job offer,

1270
00:47:14,690 --> 00:47:17,690
but an official intern offer? It's not tempting at all.

1271
00:47:18,090 --> 00:47:19,430
I'd still appreciate it.

1272
00:47:19,730 --> 00:47:21,660
I'd want my own intern.

1273
00:47:22,900 --> 00:47:26,029
(Great job during your internship.)

1274
00:47:26,030 --> 00:47:28,940
(A week later)

1275
00:47:30,070 --> 00:47:31,170
Hi.

1276
00:47:31,440 --> 00:47:33,239
- Hi.
- Hi.

1277
00:47:33,240 --> 00:47:35,109
(It's the 1st day of the 2nd training.)

1278
00:47:35,110 --> 00:47:37,110
Why are you already wearing rubber boots?

1279
00:47:41,050 --> 00:47:42,120
I have a bad feeling.

1280
00:47:42,350 --> 00:47:45,950
(The production crew's greeting is rough from the start.)

1281
00:47:46,290 --> 00:47:47,390
Dirt is already on it.

1282
00:47:48,560 --> 00:47:52,730
(While Kyung Soo is becoming more and more anxious)

1283
00:47:58,100 --> 00:48:01,540
(One man is running at full speed.)

1284
00:48:02,770 --> 00:48:03,840
You've gained weight.

1285
00:48:04,210 --> 00:48:05,769
- What?
- You've gained weight.

1286
00:48:05,770 --> 00:48:07,079
(Kwang Soo has arrived.)

1287
00:48:07,080 --> 00:48:08,140
- Kwang Soo.
- What?

1288
00:48:09,810 --> 00:48:11,149
(Cut the talk, and look.)

1289
00:48:11,150 --> 00:48:12,150
What?

1290
00:48:14,120 --> 00:48:15,680
- What?
- Look at their shoes.

1291
00:48:16,750 --> 00:48:18,020
Is that poop on the shoes?

1292
00:48:18,320 --> 00:48:20,490
No, it's part of the design.

1293
00:48:20,660 --> 00:48:21,660
- Vintage style?
- Yes.

1294
00:48:22,860 --> 00:48:24,460
You deliberately smeared poop on them?

1295
00:48:25,960 --> 00:48:29,130
(The production crew doesn't even try to hide it now.)

1296
00:48:29,460 --> 00:48:30,569
You got tanned.

1297
00:48:30,570 --> 00:48:32,229
- Didn't he get fat?
- What have you been up to?

1298
00:48:32,230 --> 00:48:34,000
- I got tanned, didn't I?
- What did you do?

1299
00:48:34,240 --> 00:48:35,240
(The director has a softer look now.)

1300
00:48:35,240 --> 00:48:36,240
Maybe.

1301
00:48:37,110 --> 00:48:38,170
Didn't I get tanned?

1302
00:48:39,140 --> 00:48:40,309
Tanned and fat.

1303
00:48:40,310 --> 00:48:42,310
I was taken aback when I looked in the mirror this morning.

1304
00:48:42,780 --> 00:48:43,780
Because you got fat?

1305
00:48:43,781 --> 00:48:45,180
No, because I got tanned.

1306
00:48:46,310 --> 00:48:47,349
No, rather than being tanned,

1307
00:48:47,350 --> 00:48:48,580
the fact that you gained weight is more obvious.

1308
00:48:49,420 --> 00:48:51,989
Why do you bring up getting tanned and ignore me...

1309
00:48:51,990 --> 00:48:52,990
bringing up...

1310
00:48:52,991 --> 00:48:54,860
- that you got fat?
- Just how fat did I get?

1311
00:48:55,520 --> 00:48:58,090
(The two bicker as soon as they meet.)

1312
00:48:58,430 --> 00:48:59,430
Let's go.

1313
00:48:59,960 --> 00:49:01,359
I don't have a beer belly, okay?

1314
00:49:01,360 --> 00:49:03,160
(Heading to the training area)

1315
00:49:05,170 --> 00:49:07,000
I heard Woo Bin's shoot starts today.

1316
00:49:08,370 --> 00:49:09,939
- After a break?
- What?

1317
00:49:09,940 --> 00:49:11,909
- After a short break?
- Yes.

1318
00:49:11,910 --> 00:49:13,340
(Woo Bin can't join the training due to scheduling conflicts.)

1319
00:49:13,810 --> 00:49:16,640
A field was rented out to start the shoot today.

1320
00:49:16,880 --> 00:49:17,880
I see.

1321
00:49:19,080 --> 00:49:20,580
Is he playing a game?

1322
00:49:24,590 --> 00:49:25,790
It's a baseball drama.

1323
00:49:25,990 --> 00:49:26,990
Is it?

1324
00:49:27,790 --> 00:49:30,930
- I didn't know.
- What did you think...

1325
00:49:31,760 --> 00:49:32,760
we were talking about until now?

1326
00:49:33,090 --> 00:49:36,259
I knew he was shooting a drama.

1327
00:49:36,260 --> 00:49:38,570
He kept talking about renting out a field.

1328
00:49:39,630 --> 00:49:42,300
Force yourself to ask me things.

1329
00:49:43,100 --> 00:49:44,110
About what you're doing?

1330
00:49:44,210 --> 00:49:45,470
Well, you know...

1331
00:49:46,270 --> 00:49:47,539
If you're not sure about something,

1332
00:49:47,540 --> 00:49:49,010
ask me even if you're forcing yourself.

1333
00:49:49,640 --> 00:49:51,110
Why does that upset you?

1334
00:49:52,610 --> 00:49:54,319
It's something like,

1335
00:49:54,320 --> 00:49:55,380
"What did you eat?"

1336
00:49:56,120 --> 00:49:57,719
You may not be curious,

1337
00:49:57,720 --> 00:49:58,850
but it's just manners.

1338
00:50:00,090 --> 00:50:01,090
I see.

1339
00:50:01,260 --> 00:50:03,859
Are you a robot or something for me to explain such things?

1340
00:50:03,860 --> 00:50:04,930
(Are you a robot or something?)

1341
00:50:06,560 --> 00:50:07,730
You have to explain for me to know.

1342
00:50:08,760 --> 00:50:11,230
(Thinking)

1343
00:50:11,470 --> 00:50:13,069
What are you working on this time?

1344
00:50:13,070 --> 00:50:14,570
- What?
- What are you?

1345
00:50:15,600 --> 00:50:17,470
- What do you mean?
- Your upcoming work.

1346
00:50:17,940 --> 00:50:19,040
- What I'm doing?
- Yes.

1347
00:50:20,310 --> 00:50:22,239
- How many times must I tell you?
- Sorry?

1348
00:50:22,240 --> 00:50:23,509
- How many times must I tell you?
- I know who's in it,

1349
00:50:23,510 --> 00:50:24,749
but I'm asking...

1350
00:50:24,750 --> 00:50:25,980
what kind of role you're playing.

1351
00:50:26,650 --> 00:50:27,980
It didn't seem ordinary.

1352
00:50:28,980 --> 00:50:30,320
That mountain looks cool.

1353
00:50:31,020 --> 00:50:32,020
What is it?

1354
00:50:32,520 --> 00:50:33,689
It's a stone mountain.

1355
00:50:33,690 --> 00:50:35,590
(Almost at the ranch as they chatted away)

1356
00:50:36,390 --> 00:50:37,529
Should I give them a call first?

1357
00:50:37,530 --> 00:50:41,400
(They call before arriving at the ranch.)

1358
00:50:41,830 --> 00:50:43,560
CEO Nam Hoon.

1359
00:50:45,400 --> 00:50:47,469
(CEO Nam Hoon)

1360
00:50:47,470 --> 00:50:48,840
I haven't heard this in a while.

1361
00:50:50,340 --> 00:50:51,670
It suits a ranch.

1362
00:50:52,240 --> 00:50:53,640
He's not picking up.

1363
00:50:54,840 --> 00:50:56,109
Hello?

1364
00:50:56,110 --> 00:50:57,610
Hello, sir.

1365
00:50:58,280 --> 00:50:59,280
Hi.

1366
00:50:59,750 --> 00:51:01,649
We're CEO Lee Kwang Soo...

1367
00:51:01,650 --> 00:51:04,849
and Director Doh Kyung Soo of KKPP Food.

1368
00:51:04,850 --> 00:51:06,119
Right, hi.

1369
00:51:06,120 --> 00:51:07,189
Hi.

1370
00:51:07,190 --> 00:51:10,220
We're just around the corner.

1371
00:51:10,690 --> 00:51:13,259
- I see.
- Should we head to the ranch?

1372
00:51:13,260 --> 00:51:14,960
Or where should we go?

1373
00:51:15,630 --> 00:51:16,630
Let's see.

1374
00:51:16,900 --> 00:51:19,869
- You should come to the ranch.
- I see.

1375
00:51:19,870 --> 00:51:21,869
- Okay.
- Our ranch is 462,810m² in size.

1376
00:51:21,870 --> 00:51:22,940
Oh, my.

1377
00:51:23,340 --> 00:51:25,369
Even with the address, it's hard to find me...

1378
00:51:25,370 --> 00:51:26,469
as the street number...

1379
00:51:26,470 --> 00:51:28,079
- doesn't cover the ranch.
- It's 462,810m²?

1380
00:51:28,080 --> 00:51:29,109
I see.

1381
00:51:29,110 --> 00:51:31,049
I'll send you an exact spot,

1382
00:51:31,050 --> 00:51:32,249
so come look for me.

1383
00:51:32,250 --> 00:51:33,849
- Got it.
- Okay.

1384
00:51:33,850 --> 00:51:35,349
I'm at the top of the ranch,

1385
00:51:35,350 --> 00:51:37,249
so I can't go down to pick you up.

1386
00:51:37,250 --> 00:51:39,149
- I see.
- I'll send you my exact spot.

1387
00:51:39,150 --> 00:51:40,250
- Got it.
- Wait.

1388
00:51:40,690 --> 00:51:42,560
You're not willing to come down, are you?

1389
00:51:42,890 --> 00:51:45,090
You're currently working, right?

1390
00:51:45,660 --> 00:51:47,699
Yes, I'm currently working at the ranch.

1391
00:51:47,700 --> 00:51:48,700
I see.

1392
00:51:48,701 --> 00:51:50,700
So I'm not willing to go down.

1393
00:51:51,800 --> 00:51:54,100
Got it. I asked just in case.

1394
00:51:54,600 --> 00:51:56,269
- Right.
- He's the firm type.

1395
00:51:56,270 --> 00:51:58,209
- Yes?
- I'll see you in a bit.

1396
00:51:58,210 --> 00:51:59,539
- Okay.
- Bye.

1397
00:51:59,540 --> 00:52:00,540
- Bye.
- Thank you.

1398
00:52:00,540 --> 00:52:01,540
(After the call with the CEO)

1399
00:52:02,310 --> 00:52:03,480
- It's here.
- It's here.

1400
00:52:03,540 --> 00:52:05,080
(The CEO's exact location has arrived.)

1401
00:52:06,350 --> 00:52:08,219
We're here right now.

1402
00:52:08,220 --> 00:52:09,220
This is the place.

1403
00:52:10,220 --> 00:52:12,120
It even has the route. We can even know the route.

1404
00:52:12,920 --> 00:52:14,759
- Let's set this as the destination.
- Route.

1405
00:52:14,760 --> 00:52:16,760
(Route)

1406
00:52:18,060 --> 00:52:23,730
(Taking the recommended route)

1407
00:52:24,570 --> 00:52:26,099
If the CEO moves,

1408
00:52:26,100 --> 00:52:27,469
so will his location.

1409
00:52:27,470 --> 00:52:28,639
Yes, it'll keep moving.

1410
00:52:28,640 --> 00:52:30,140
- It'll change the destination.
- Correct.

1411
00:52:30,910 --> 00:52:33,070
Can we take the car to the location?

1412
00:52:33,610 --> 00:52:35,039
If we arrive at the gate...

1413
00:52:35,040 --> 00:52:37,249
- The setting...
- and change it to "walking,"

1414
00:52:37,250 --> 00:52:38,650
it'll tell us how to get there on foot.

1415
00:52:39,280 --> 00:52:42,020
(And so, they head to the horse ranch.)

1416
00:52:42,850 --> 00:52:43,919
If it's 528,930m²...

1417
00:52:43,920 --> 00:52:45,820
- No, if it's 561,980m², - Yes?

1418
00:52:46,150 --> 00:52:47,520
how many horses must there be?

1419
00:52:48,660 --> 00:52:50,660
The last farm had...

1420
00:52:52,630 --> 00:52:54,700
- Wasn't it 120 cows?
- over 100 cows.

1421
00:52:55,160 --> 00:52:57,599
The size is sixfold.

1422
00:52:57,600 --> 00:52:59,199
There's a speed bump near here.

1423
00:52:59,200 --> 00:53:00,900
Don't tell me he has 600 horses.

1424
00:53:03,270 --> 00:53:05,440
- Maybe 500...
- But the thing is,

1425
00:53:05,910 --> 00:53:07,240
dairy farms...

1426
00:53:07,810 --> 00:53:09,339
have to produce milk,

1427
00:53:09,340 --> 00:53:10,880
- hence the many cows.
- Right.

1428
00:53:11,250 --> 00:53:13,110
- But this ranch...
- You're right.

1429
00:53:13,210 --> 00:53:14,580
With horses...

1430
00:53:15,980 --> 00:53:17,820
What could you do with horses?

1431
00:53:18,150 --> 00:53:19,150
Horses.

1432
00:53:19,750 --> 00:53:20,860
What do you do with horses?

1433
00:53:21,020 --> 00:53:22,619
(Curious about the horse ranch's profit structure)

1434
00:53:22,620 --> 00:53:23,890
Why raise horses?

1435
00:53:25,160 --> 00:53:26,730
Aren't horses bigger than cows?

1436
00:53:27,330 --> 00:53:28,659
Soon, you should turn left.

1437
00:53:28,660 --> 00:53:32,730
From what I remember, horses are taller.

1438
00:53:33,200 --> 00:53:35,370
Actually, they're similar in size.

1439
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:37,640
The difference isn't huge.

1440
00:53:37,870 --> 00:53:39,009
Have you never ridden a horse?

1441
00:53:39,010 --> 00:53:41,540
(Have you never ridden a horse?)

1442
00:53:42,040 --> 00:53:43,210
Did you never ride one?

1443
00:53:44,380 --> 00:53:46,910
Rather than riding one,

1444
00:53:47,210 --> 00:53:48,219
- Leading one?
- my roles were mostly...

1445
00:53:48,220 --> 00:53:49,220
leading a horse.

1446
00:53:49,650 --> 00:53:50,650
Even so, you'd know.

1447
00:53:50,651 --> 00:53:51,890
People like you would be the one who's riding it.

1448
00:53:52,790 --> 00:53:55,259
(Getting upset while saying it)

1449
00:53:55,260 --> 00:53:57,330
I usually led the horse.

1450
00:53:59,590 --> 00:54:01,659
I even learned horseback riding because I was told to.

1451
00:54:01,660 --> 00:54:03,330
Really? But you didn't ride one?

1452
00:54:03,830 --> 00:54:04,970
But I just led it around.

1453
00:54:09,270 --> 00:54:10,300
We're here.

1454
00:54:11,740 --> 00:54:12,869
Wait. Gosh.

1455
00:54:12,870 --> 00:54:14,939
It's telling you...

1456
00:54:14,940 --> 00:54:16,240
- To park nearby.
- to park nearby.

1457
00:54:17,380 --> 00:54:19,210
He must be somewhere around here.

1458
00:54:19,650 --> 00:54:20,750
There are horses over there.

1459
00:54:21,380 --> 00:54:22,380
- Is this the place?
- Yes.

1460
00:54:23,620 --> 00:54:25,320
This seems to be the location.

1461
00:54:26,390 --> 00:54:27,659
- Let's go.
- This is the gate.

1462
00:54:27,660 --> 00:54:28,719
We're here.

1463
00:54:28,720 --> 00:54:31,760
(They arrived at the horse ranch.)

1464
00:54:32,230 --> 00:54:33,259
He's over here.

1465
00:54:33,260 --> 00:54:35,259
(Route)

1466
00:54:35,260 --> 00:54:36,660
We could enter through there.

1467
00:54:37,800 --> 00:54:39,170
There's a gate right here.

1468
00:54:39,800 --> 00:54:42,500
(Finally going into the horse ranch)

1469
00:54:43,500 --> 00:54:45,140
It sure is huge.

1470
00:54:45,870 --> 00:54:48,610
(Finally going into the horse ranch)

1471
00:54:49,610 --> 00:54:51,380
It sure is huge.

1472
00:54:53,180 --> 00:54:54,180
It's really big.

1473
00:54:54,181 --> 00:54:57,220
(As soon as they walk into the ranch,)

1474
00:54:57,420 --> 00:54:58,549
How pretty.

1475
00:54:58,550 --> 00:55:00,660
(a vast grassland lies before them.)

1476
00:55:00,860 --> 00:55:02,620
It's huge. Look over there!

1477
00:55:02,890 --> 00:55:04,229
Aren't those real horses?

1478
00:55:04,230 --> 00:55:05,390
(And in the middle of the grassland,)

1479
00:55:06,160 --> 00:55:07,289
They're running!

1480
00:55:07,290 --> 00:55:10,300
(the horses run freely.)

1481
00:55:11,430 --> 00:55:12,730
This is so cool.

1482
00:55:15,970 --> 00:55:18,640
(A tranquil scene painted by the horses)

1483
00:55:18,840 --> 00:55:21,480
Should we give him a call, Kwang Soo?

1484
00:55:22,740 --> 00:55:23,740
(However, it's hard...)

1485
00:55:23,741 --> 00:55:24,810
We can't find the CEO.

1486
00:55:25,750 --> 00:55:26,809
Let's call him.

1487
00:55:26,810 --> 00:55:29,320
(to find the CEO on the vast ranch.)

1488
00:55:33,550 --> 00:55:34,560
It's like...

1489
00:55:36,120 --> 00:55:37,990
- Yes, hello?
- Hi, sir.

1490
00:55:38,260 --> 00:55:40,530
- Yes?
- We're at the ranch.

1491
00:55:41,060 --> 00:55:42,659
- Are you?
- Yes.

1492
00:55:42,660 --> 00:55:45,099
I'll send you my location,

1493
00:55:45,100 --> 00:55:46,869
so can you come here?

1494
00:55:46,870 --> 00:55:48,639
Okay, please send it to us.

1495
00:55:48,640 --> 00:55:50,270
- Okay.
- Great.

1496
00:55:51,640 --> 00:55:52,840
(End of the call)

1497
00:55:53,910 --> 00:55:55,309
He sounds just like he did earlier.

1498
00:55:55,310 --> 00:55:57,239
- Is he an AI?
- Then...

1499
00:55:57,240 --> 00:55:58,310
(Questioning if he's an AI)

1500
00:55:58,450 --> 00:55:59,610
He's here!

1501
00:56:00,450 --> 00:56:01,479
He's over there!

1502
00:56:01,480 --> 00:56:02,480
(The new location has arrived.)

1503
00:56:04,850 --> 00:56:06,190
- Kwang Soo.
- He must be over there!

1504
00:56:08,220 --> 00:56:09,689
(Neighing)

1505
00:56:09,690 --> 00:56:11,030
The sound of a horse!

1506
00:56:12,260 --> 00:56:13,260
Wait.

1507
00:56:13,261 --> 00:56:14,600
It must be him, Kwang Soo.

1508
00:56:15,230 --> 00:56:17,399
(A mysterious man is standing with a horse.)

1509
00:56:17,400 --> 00:56:18,500
How do we get there?

1510
00:56:19,530 --> 00:56:20,840
Sir... Can I shout?

1511
00:56:21,370 --> 00:56:22,439
Nope!

1512
00:56:22,440 --> 00:56:25,269
(Shouting)

1513
00:56:25,270 --> 00:56:26,670
Can you actually shout that loudly?

1514
00:56:28,763 --> 00:56:29,640
Nope!

1515
00:56:30,110 --> 00:56:31,110
(Shouting)

1516
00:56:31,710 --> 00:56:34,220
- Who is he shouting at?
- He must be telling it not to come.

1517
00:56:37,020 --> 00:56:38,290
Hi.

1518
00:56:38,320 --> 00:56:40,249
- Hi.
- Are you CEO Nam Hoon?

1519
00:56:40,250 --> 00:56:41,519
- Yes.
- Hi.

1520
00:56:41,520 --> 00:56:42,759
(Kim Nam Hoon, CEO of the ranch)

1521
00:56:42,760 --> 00:56:44,590
- Hi.
- Nice to meet you.

1522
00:56:44,830 --> 00:56:46,160
What were you doing just now?

1523
00:56:46,230 --> 00:56:47,700
Today...

1524
00:56:48,300 --> 00:56:50,230
is ipmok day.

1525
00:56:50,630 --> 00:56:51,829
- Ipmok?
- Ipmok...

1526
00:56:51,830 --> 00:56:54,270
is letting the horses out in the field.

1527
00:56:55,400 --> 00:56:56,440
They must be so happy.

1528
00:56:57,570 --> 00:56:58,970
The horses look free.

1529
00:57:01,580 --> 00:57:02,610
Jacy.

1530
00:57:03,440 --> 00:57:05,550
Come here. Good girl. Hurry.

1531
00:57:06,110 --> 00:57:07,679
Hurry. Come.

1532
00:57:07,680 --> 00:57:09,149
- Good girl.
- She comes when you call her.

1533
00:57:09,150 --> 00:57:11,290
- The horse is pregnant.
- She's pregnant.

1534
00:57:12,520 --> 00:57:14,689
If you approach from the front, she'll think you're a threat.

1535
00:57:14,690 --> 00:57:16,490
- Okay.
- Turn around.

1536
00:57:16,820 --> 00:57:18,389
She'll sniff you first. Okay.

1537
00:57:18,390 --> 00:57:19,729
(Stretching his arms out to Jacy)

1538
00:57:19,730 --> 00:57:20,730
That's it.

1539
00:57:20,731 --> 00:57:22,759
(Looking away)

1540
00:57:22,760 --> 00:57:24,130
You must not smell nice.

1541
00:57:24,630 --> 00:57:25,870
- I just washed my hands.
- We washed our hands.

1542
00:57:25,900 --> 00:57:28,840
(Admirable Kyung Soo is anxious.)

1543
00:57:29,800 --> 00:57:32,370
I'll give you a sweat scraper.

1544
00:57:32,740 --> 00:57:34,510
Try brushing Jacy.

1545
00:57:35,910 --> 00:57:37,650
After that, touch her.

1546
00:57:39,910 --> 00:57:41,519
- What's her name?
- Jacy.

1547
00:57:41,520 --> 00:57:42,949
- Jessie?
- Jacy.

1548
00:57:42,950 --> 00:57:44,190
- Jacy?
- Yes.

1549
00:57:44,220 --> 00:57:45,319
Jacy.

1550
00:57:45,320 --> 00:57:47,449
(A nervous first bond with Jacy)

1551
00:57:47,450 --> 00:57:48,719
Each horse is different.

1552
00:57:48,720 --> 00:57:50,860
(Trying to bond with Jacy again)

1553
00:57:50,990 --> 00:57:52,889
- It's so soft.
- It's okay.

1554
00:57:52,890 --> 00:57:54,360
Go ahead and give her a hug.

1555
00:57:56,300 --> 00:57:58,069
She's so soft.

1556
00:57:58,070 --> 00:58:00,730
- It's my first time...
- The texture of a horse's fur...

1557
00:58:01,470 --> 00:58:03,239
that I had in mind was kind of rough.

1558
00:58:03,240 --> 00:58:04,670
Is that so?

1559
00:58:05,240 --> 00:58:06,240
Nice.

1560
00:58:06,241 --> 00:58:08,809
It's my first time touching a horse. Never did I think...

1561
00:58:08,810 --> 00:58:09,940
I'd get a chance to touch one.

1562
00:58:11,250 --> 00:58:12,649
It's warm.

1563
00:58:12,650 --> 00:58:14,750
That horse is running in its dream.

1564
00:58:15,220 --> 00:58:16,479
(Laughing)

1565
00:58:16,480 --> 00:58:18,620
- Is it sleeping right now?
- How cute.

1566
00:58:20,020 --> 00:58:21,319
It's really small.

1567
00:58:21,320 --> 00:58:22,859
It's not a foal.

1568
00:58:22,860 --> 00:58:24,889
It's a Shetland pony.

1569
00:58:24,890 --> 00:58:27,160
- So it's a pony.
- It's the smallest breed.

1570
00:58:28,430 --> 00:58:29,830
It's only four days old?

1571
00:58:30,200 --> 00:58:31,499
Look at it drinking milk.

1572
00:58:31,500 --> 00:58:33,269
So it's drinking milk.

1573
00:58:33,270 --> 00:58:34,640
It's devouring it.

1574
00:58:35,100 --> 00:58:36,669
The mother is staying still.

1575
00:58:36,670 --> 00:58:38,340
The mother stays still for it.

1576
00:58:39,410 --> 00:58:41,039
Kwang Soo, it's drinking with its eyes closed.

1577
00:58:41,040 --> 00:58:42,140
(Sticking out)

1578
00:58:44,380 --> 00:58:46,410
(Reaching out)

1579
00:58:46,910 --> 00:58:48,620
Stay still, and it'll approach you.

1580
00:58:50,020 --> 00:58:51,219
(Who will it go to?)

1581
00:58:51,220 --> 00:58:53,590
Who will it choose? Oh, my.

1582
00:58:54,560 --> 00:58:56,860
(Hesitating)

1583
00:58:57,730 --> 00:59:01,660
(Trainee Kwang Soo has been chosen.)

1584
00:59:03,400 --> 00:59:05,970
(Savoring Kwang Soo's finger)

1585
00:59:06,600 --> 00:59:07,770
It doesn't have teeth.

1586
00:59:08,740 --> 00:59:10,040
No, it has no teeth.

1587
00:59:14,980 --> 00:59:17,509
(Brushing after bonding with the ponies)

1588
00:59:17,510 --> 00:59:18,610
A gift, Kwang Soo.

1589
00:59:20,510 --> 00:59:21,650
Thank...

1590
00:59:22,780 --> 00:59:23,780
(Startled)

1591
00:59:23,781 --> 00:59:25,619
(A sudden horse poop gift)

1592
00:59:25,620 --> 00:59:27,889
- Sir...
- It was horse poop.

1593
00:59:27,890 --> 00:59:28,890
Why did you...

1594
00:59:28,890 --> 00:59:29,890
(Startled by the unexpected horse poop)

1595
00:59:29,890 --> 00:59:30,890
That startled me.

1596
00:59:30,891 --> 00:59:32,060
- But...
- Yes?

1597
00:59:32,290 --> 00:59:34,030
Try smelling it, Kyung Soo.

1598
00:59:34,830 --> 00:59:35,860
It doesn't smell at all.

1599
00:59:36,400 --> 00:59:37,459
It has no smell.

1600
00:59:37,460 --> 00:59:38,570
You've got poop on your nose.

1601
00:59:39,170 --> 00:59:41,340
- It doesn't smell.
- It doesn't, right?

1602
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:43,069
The poop doesn't smell.

1603
00:59:43,070 --> 00:59:44,200
(Horse poop is odorless even when it's on his nose.)

1604
00:59:45,012 --> 00:59:46,240
Should I try mashing it up?

1605
00:59:46,740 --> 00:59:47,810
Here, smell it.

1606
00:59:48,140 --> 00:59:49,140
(Shocked)

1607
00:59:49,141 --> 00:59:50,779
- Smell of dirt.
- You can only smell grass.

1608
00:59:50,780 --> 00:59:51,780
How come?

1609
00:59:51,781 --> 00:59:55,420
This is a grazing ranch, so the poop doesn't smell.

1610
00:59:56,260 --> 00:59:58,860
See these seeds? Barley seeds.

1611
00:59:59,320 --> 01:00:01,159
These seeds...

1612
01:00:01,160 --> 01:00:02,487
grow back into grass.

1613
01:00:02,720 --> 01:00:04,089
And so, the poop doesn't smell.

1614
01:00:04,090 --> 01:00:06,560
But... Look at the director.

1615
01:00:06,760 --> 01:00:08,130
Stop enjoying it.

1616
01:00:09,130 --> 01:00:10,199
(Scratching)

1617
01:00:10,200 --> 01:00:11,630
Take videos of us.

1618
01:00:11,900 --> 01:00:14,000
(Indulging his own wishes while working)

1619
01:00:14,200 --> 01:00:15,522
How adorable.

1620
01:00:15,547 --> 01:00:16,669
- Aren't they?
- Are there any precautions...

1621
01:00:16,670 --> 01:00:17,909
we should take...

1622
01:00:17,910 --> 01:00:19,140
- around horses?
- Precautions?

1623
01:00:19,340 --> 01:00:21,609
Try not to overstimulate the horses.

1624
01:00:21,610 --> 01:00:22,640
(While the CEO is explaining the precautions)

1625
01:00:23,040 --> 01:00:24,080
Give me a minute.

1626
01:00:25,150 --> 01:00:26,179
Yes?

1627
01:00:26,180 --> 01:00:27,879
(Taking a call out of the blue)

1628
01:00:27,915 --> 01:00:29,955
I can't make deliveries today because I have a prior schedule.

1629
01:00:29,980 --> 01:00:32,549
- Deliver what?
- Leave me a message.

1630
01:00:32,550 --> 01:00:34,790
It'll be 40 dollars to Daejeong-eup.

1631
01:00:35,690 --> 01:00:37,060
- Leave me a message.
- Can someone...

1632
01:00:37,190 --> 01:00:39,360
really not care about the cameras like him?

1633
01:00:39,930 --> 01:00:41,299
Sorry. Today...

1634
01:00:41,300 --> 01:00:43,359
We collect the manure...

1635
01:00:43,360 --> 01:00:44,929
and sell it as fertilizer.

1636
01:00:44,930 --> 01:00:47,669
- I put it up on Karrot.
- Delivery for fertilizer?

1637
01:00:47,670 --> 01:00:49,839
- So you do Karrot.
- Yes.

1638
01:00:49,840 --> 01:00:52,710
I sell poop to buy horse feed.

1639
01:00:53,240 --> 01:00:54,609
I still need to make money.

1640
01:00:54,610 --> 01:00:55,739
Of course.

1641
01:00:55,740 --> 01:00:57,640
I was actually curious about that.

1642
01:00:57,910 --> 01:01:00,209
Everything is great,

1643
01:01:00,210 --> 01:01:03,219
but both the horses and the CEO need food to eat.

1644
01:01:03,220 --> 01:01:04,650
You need some sort of profit.

1645
01:01:05,390 --> 01:01:07,650
The profit comes from educational programs.

1646
01:01:07,990 --> 01:01:10,690
We're a pasture-based eco-livestock farm.

1647
01:01:11,160 --> 01:01:13,230
It's the first in Korea to take care...

1648
01:01:13,660 --> 01:01:15,799
- of retired racehorses.
- Retired racehorses? Amazing.

1649
01:01:15,800 --> 01:01:16,800
- Awesome.
- So...

1650
01:01:16,801 --> 01:01:19,169
We give them showers,

1651
01:01:19,170 --> 01:01:20,929
lie together on the grassland, and more.

1652
01:01:20,930 --> 01:01:23,499
The horses help me make a living.

1653
01:01:23,500 --> 01:01:24,870
Why don't you...

1654
01:01:25,370 --> 01:01:26,839
- gather the poop today...
- Okay.

1655
01:01:26,840 --> 01:01:28,809
- and sell it...
- Gather poop?

1656
01:01:28,810 --> 01:01:29,839
on Karrot?

1657
01:01:29,840 --> 01:01:30,840
(Looking gloomy at the poop news)

1658
01:01:30,841 --> 01:01:32,079
(Disappointed)

1659
01:01:32,080 --> 01:01:34,420
- Is it not okay?
- No, it's fine.

1660
01:01:34,920 --> 01:01:35,920
Poop...

1661
01:01:37,320 --> 01:01:40,320
We cleaned a ton of poop...

1662
01:01:40,650 --> 01:01:41,690
last week.

1663
01:01:42,160 --> 01:01:43,319
- Poop...
- Is that so?

1664
01:01:43,320 --> 01:01:45,560
We only just escaped from cleaning poop for a week!

1665
01:01:46,460 --> 01:01:47,899
It was cows last week.

1666
01:01:47,900 --> 01:01:49,199
- Really?
- Yes.

1667
01:01:49,200 --> 01:01:50,629
Cows? Then...

1668
01:01:50,630 --> 01:01:52,429
- Poop...
- Please...

1669
01:01:52,430 --> 01:01:53,899
clean the poop off your nose first.

1670
01:01:53,900 --> 01:01:55,940
- Do I have poop on my nose? Where?
- You do.

1671
01:01:55,970 --> 01:01:57,340
It's from smelling poop earlier.

1672
01:01:58,810 --> 01:02:02,109
(Cleaning the horse poop off his nose as if it's nothing)

1673
01:02:02,110 --> 01:02:04,310
You know that? I just touched your nose...

1674
01:02:05,010 --> 01:02:06,680
Give me a second. Nope!

1675
01:02:11,750 --> 01:02:13,150
Achick!

1676
01:02:14,190 --> 01:02:16,790
(Running to wherever the horses are)

1677
01:02:17,220 --> 01:02:18,630
- What?
- It must be a prohibited place.

1678
01:02:18,860 --> 01:02:19,889
Where?

1679
01:02:19,890 --> 01:02:21,660
(The CEO is unpredictable.)

1680
01:02:22,260 --> 01:02:24,059
(The ranch tour resumes.)

1681
01:02:24,060 --> 01:02:25,599
These horses can graze freely.

1682
01:02:25,600 --> 01:02:26,930
- I see.
- Right.

1683
01:02:29,300 --> 01:02:31,169
That's a Shetland pony. It's cute, isn't it?

1684
01:02:31,170 --> 01:02:32,909
It's spotted.

1685
01:02:32,910 --> 01:02:33,910
It's...

1686
01:02:34,410 --> 01:02:36,110
- How cute.
- It's like a Dalmatian.

1687
01:02:37,140 --> 01:02:38,510
Like a wild horse.

1688
01:02:40,450 --> 01:02:42,649
They just roam around freely.

1689
01:02:42,650 --> 01:02:43,750
(The horses wandering through the pasture like wild horses)

1690
01:02:46,020 --> 01:02:47,319
How big is this place?

1691
01:02:47,320 --> 01:02:48,320
It's 462,810 m².

1692
01:02:48,321 --> 01:02:49,559
- Gosh.
- It's 462,810 m²?

1693
01:02:49,560 --> 01:02:50,820
(Exclaiming)

1694
01:02:53,090 --> 01:02:54,930
CEO Kim,

1695
01:02:55,030 --> 01:02:57,299
how many horses are in this area?

1696
01:02:57,300 --> 01:03:00,099
Currently, we have a total of 53 horses.

1697
01:03:00,100 --> 01:03:01,500
(They're caring for a total of 53 horses.)

1698
01:03:01,940 --> 01:03:03,199
It's really huge.

1699
01:03:03,200 --> 01:03:06,740
(Across the vast pasture of 462,810m²,)

1700
01:03:09,240 --> 01:03:10,840
This is amazing.

1701
01:03:12,310 --> 01:03:16,320
(53 horses run freely.)

1702
01:03:16,920 --> 01:03:18,720
It's a paradise for horses.

1703
01:03:20,920 --> 01:03:21,920
They're having fun.

1704
01:03:21,921 --> 01:03:23,290
They're so beautiful.

1705
01:03:26,830 --> 01:03:28,259
Look, that one came running out.

1706
01:03:28,260 --> 01:03:29,500
(The horses emerge from the woods at the sound of ma.)

1707
01:03:30,430 --> 01:03:31,830
Benny, where were you?

1708
01:03:32,300 --> 01:03:33,300
Coco.

1709
01:03:33,500 --> 01:03:34,540
What have you guys...

1710
01:03:34,640 --> 01:03:37,300
been up to in the woods?

1711
01:03:38,040 --> 01:03:39,669
This doesn't feel real.

1712
01:03:39,670 --> 01:03:40,670
I know.

1713
01:03:40,740 --> 01:03:43,210
It's what you usually say to dogs at home.

1714
01:03:44,080 --> 01:03:46,079
"What did you eat?"

1715
01:03:46,080 --> 01:03:47,710
He's saying it to horses.

1716
01:03:50,280 --> 01:03:52,449
We got here not so long ago, but it's already so relaxing.

1717
01:03:52,450 --> 01:03:53,450
- Right?
- Yes.

1718
01:03:53,690 --> 01:03:56,689
Let's work today while enjoying the green scenery.

1719
01:03:56,690 --> 01:03:57,720
Okay.

1720
01:03:58,590 --> 01:04:00,130
- I'm an expert at cleaning up poop.
- Okay.

1721
01:04:02,430 --> 01:04:03,629
- Look, Kwang Soo.
- Look over there.

1722
01:04:03,630 --> 01:04:05,030
- My gosh.
- Do you see the horses?

1723
01:04:06,300 --> 01:04:07,899
This place looks exotic.

1724
01:04:07,900 --> 01:04:08,969
It's fascinating.

1725
01:04:08,970 --> 01:04:11,169
It's hard to believe there's a place like this in Korea.

1726
01:04:11,170 --> 01:04:12,910
(An area for horses visible through the green barley fields)

1727
01:04:13,340 --> 01:04:14,840
Horses that were recently rescued,

1728
01:04:14,940 --> 01:04:17,540
sick, or abused are protected...

1729
01:04:18,450 --> 01:04:22,080
in a special care area.

1730
01:04:22,980 --> 01:04:26,149
The first priority is helping them gain weight.

1731
01:04:26,150 --> 01:04:27,389
(Gaining weight is the most important for the horses.)

1732
01:04:27,390 --> 01:04:30,789
They wear halters and are kept with basic lead ropes.

1733
01:04:30,790 --> 01:04:32,489
(They wear halters as part of their special care routine.)

1734
01:04:32,490 --> 01:04:33,790
This is how you socialize them.

1735
01:04:35,400 --> 01:04:36,560
- Kwang Soo.
- Yes, sir.

1736
01:04:37,060 --> 01:04:39,499
(They came to meet horses in the special care zone.)

1737
01:04:39,500 --> 01:04:40,670
- They're tangerines.
- Jeju Island is famous...

1738
01:04:41,400 --> 01:04:42,670
- for tangerines.
- Yes.

1739
01:04:45,040 --> 01:04:46,239
This isn't for you.

1740
01:04:46,240 --> 01:04:48,210
- Is it for horses?
- It's for horses.

1741
01:04:48,310 --> 01:04:49,310
Really?

1742
01:04:50,910 --> 01:04:51,950
Arthur.

1743
01:04:52,880 --> 01:04:54,380
It's the biggest horse on earth.

1744
01:04:54,780 --> 01:04:57,250
(The biggest horse on earth?)

1745
01:04:57,420 --> 01:04:58,589
(Gasping)

1746
01:04:58,590 --> 01:05:00,890
- What is this?
- It looks amazing.

1747
01:05:01,890 --> 01:05:03,119
It's really big.

1748
01:05:03,120 --> 01:05:04,120
(A presence unlike any horse they've seen before)

1749
01:05:04,121 --> 01:05:05,290
Look how thick his legs are.

1750
01:05:05,543 --> 01:05:06,643
His hooves are this big.

1751
01:05:06,860 --> 01:05:07,860
Our Arthur weighs one ton.

1752
01:05:07,861 --> 01:05:11,400
That's why I told you not to get stepped on by him.

1753
01:05:12,130 --> 01:05:13,570
If you get stepped on by him...

1754
01:05:15,500 --> 01:05:16,950
Isn't this horse different?

1755
01:05:17,515 --> 01:05:19,345
Compared to the tiny horse before...

1756
01:05:19,370 --> 01:05:21,169
You can hear a thud every step he takes.

1757
01:05:21,170 --> 01:05:23,640
All right, give him a tangerine.

1758
01:05:24,327 --> 01:05:25,049
Put it on your palm.

1759
01:05:25,050 --> 01:05:26,450
(Licking it off)

1760
01:05:27,950 --> 01:05:30,150
If you hold a cup underneath, you can collect the juice.

1761
01:05:30,850 --> 01:05:32,520
You'll see the sword of Excalibur here.

1762
01:05:33,290 --> 01:05:34,490
This is King Arthur.

1763
01:05:36,120 --> 01:05:39,260
The horse's mane looks like it's been permed.

1764
01:05:39,490 --> 01:05:42,030
(Arthur's curly mane is his another charming feature.)

1765
01:05:42,600 --> 01:05:44,100
It sounds like a blender.

1766
01:05:46,700 --> 01:05:47,700
Grab here.

1767
01:05:48,500 --> 01:05:49,570
Lift your left leg.

1768
01:05:50,640 --> 01:05:52,210
- What?
- One, two, three. Jump.

1769
01:05:53,610 --> 01:05:55,180
(Mouth wide open)

1770
01:06:00,710 --> 01:06:02,079
Sir, you're making me do this...

1771
01:06:02,080 --> 01:06:04,150
(Juicing)

1772
01:06:04,950 --> 01:06:07,149
(Sitting on the horse's back)

1773
01:06:07,150 --> 01:06:08,290
It's really warm.

1774
01:06:08,490 --> 01:06:09,690
- Isn't it very warm?
- Yes.

1775
01:06:10,490 --> 01:06:12,330
When will I ever get to ride a horse like this?

1776
01:06:13,590 --> 01:06:15,030
Spread out your arms.

1777
01:06:15,460 --> 01:06:16,499
Lie down.

1778
01:06:16,500 --> 01:06:18,330
- Lie down?
- Yes.

1779
01:06:20,200 --> 01:06:21,200
Okay.

1780
01:06:21,200 --> 01:06:22,200
(He lies back and rests his back against Arthur.)

1781
01:06:22,201 --> 01:06:23,239
It's a horse bed.

1782
01:06:23,240 --> 01:06:24,740
It's really comfortable.

1783
01:06:28,240 --> 01:06:29,740
- Isn't it very comfortable?
- Yes.

1784
01:06:30,040 --> 01:06:32,150
(Patting gently)

1785
01:06:32,410 --> 01:06:34,579
Shall I turn off the heater? Isn't it too hot?

1786
01:06:34,580 --> 01:06:35,979
Yes, it's very warm.

1787
01:06:35,980 --> 01:06:36,980
Sit back up.

1788
01:06:36,981 --> 01:06:40,520
(The horse's body heat makes it cozier.)

1789
01:06:40,750 --> 01:06:41,760
Straighten your back.

1790
01:06:42,660 --> 01:06:44,359
Grab the mane here and pull it.

1791
01:06:44,360 --> 01:06:45,560
The other horse is eating them.

1792
01:06:45,790 --> 01:06:46,790
Look at him.

1793
01:06:46,791 --> 01:06:47,889
(The horse is eating something?)

1794
01:06:47,890 --> 01:06:48,900
Let him eat.

1795
01:06:50,160 --> 01:06:54,430
(Taking the opportunity to steal some tangerines)

1796
01:06:55,440 --> 01:06:57,469
My goodness.

1797
01:06:57,470 --> 01:06:59,440
- Kwang Soo, pull the horse.
- Gosh.

1798
01:07:01,980 --> 01:07:03,380
- Walk with them.
- But...

1799
01:07:03,580 --> 01:07:05,480
Okay, walk with horse.

1800
01:07:06,950 --> 01:07:08,649
But... Goodness.

1801
01:07:08,650 --> 01:07:11,790
(The King's Equerry)

1802
01:07:12,390 --> 01:07:13,820
Shouldn't I be on the horse?

1803
01:07:14,550 --> 01:07:17,619
(Somehow, it feels familiar.)

1804
01:07:17,620 --> 01:07:19,259
I'm older than him,

1805
01:07:19,260 --> 01:07:20,590
and I'm the CEO.

1806
01:07:21,230 --> 01:07:22,230
Pull him.

1807
01:07:22,560 --> 01:07:23,560
Goodness.

1808
01:07:24,630 --> 01:07:27,199
I've always done this even in a drama.

1809
01:07:27,200 --> 01:07:28,440
(Feeling triumphant)

1810
01:07:28,870 --> 01:07:32,940
Riding a huge horse like this...

1811
01:07:33,370 --> 01:07:34,370
makes me feel...

1812
01:07:35,080 --> 01:07:36,510
like a king.

1813
01:07:37,980 --> 01:07:39,649
(Kwang Soo remains silent.)

1814
01:07:39,650 --> 01:07:41,250
I really feel like a servant.

1815
01:07:42,250 --> 01:07:43,320
Arthur, here's a tangerine.

1816
01:07:43,550 --> 01:07:46,390
(He seems like a royal subject.)

1817
01:07:46,690 --> 01:07:48,190
Today's biggest highlight is...

1818
01:07:49,260 --> 01:07:51,490
Why does Kyung Soo always get the highlight moment?

1819
01:07:52,530 --> 01:07:53,590
Lift your left leg.

1820
01:07:54,760 --> 01:07:56,560
One, two, three. Jump.

1821
01:07:58,500 --> 01:08:00,130
(My goodness)

1822
01:08:02,700 --> 01:08:04,640
Hold onto Kyung Soo's waist.

1823
01:08:05,910 --> 01:08:08,680
A horse can carry about 20 percent of its own weight.

1824
01:08:09,040 --> 01:08:10,410
Since he weighs about one ton...

1825
01:08:11,910 --> 01:08:13,010
It doesn't bother him at all.

1826
01:08:14,750 --> 01:08:17,119
(He goes back to eating grass.)

1827
01:08:17,120 --> 01:08:18,190
He is so amazing.

1828
01:08:19,020 --> 01:08:20,020
Sung Joon.

1829
01:08:20,950 --> 01:08:22,090
Should I take it?

1830
01:08:22,820 --> 01:08:23,820
Give it to me.

1831
01:08:23,821 --> 01:08:25,060
(They're the senior staff at the horse ranch.)

1832
01:08:25,530 --> 01:08:27,559
How many employees do you have?

1833
01:08:27,560 --> 01:08:30,659
- My employees are Sung Joon...
- Yes.

1834
01:08:30,660 --> 01:08:32,469
and Sung Joo.

1835
01:08:32,470 --> 01:08:34,130
- I see.
- There are two of them.

1836
01:08:35,070 --> 01:08:36,500
For the next three days,

1837
01:08:36,940 --> 01:08:38,539
- you'll be working in their place.
- Right.

1838
01:08:38,540 --> 01:08:40,140
That's why both of you look so happy.

1839
01:08:41,110 --> 01:08:42,110
(Big smiles)

1840
01:08:42,111 --> 01:08:43,309
I was wondering why they were smiling.

1841
01:08:43,310 --> 01:08:45,050
It's not even a funny situation.

1842
01:08:45,980 --> 01:08:47,050
With a tangerine in their hand...

1843
01:08:47,150 --> 01:08:48,449
(Smiling)

1844
01:08:48,450 --> 01:08:49,450
They kept doing this.

1845
01:08:49,920 --> 01:08:51,820
At the thought of taking a break...

1846
01:08:51,920 --> 01:08:53,250
Right.

1847
01:08:54,290 --> 01:08:56,319
We received a lot of orders.

1848
01:08:56,320 --> 01:08:58,060
- What orders?
- Poop orders.

1849
01:08:58,360 --> 01:08:59,360
We don't have enough poop.

1850
01:08:59,361 --> 01:09:00,929
Do you mean the phone call you got?

1851
01:09:00,930 --> 01:09:03,799
We have to collect the manure and load it onto that truck.

1852
01:09:03,800 --> 01:09:05,230
- I see.
- All right.

1853
01:09:06,370 --> 01:09:09,669
(The horses roam freely throughout the pasture.)

1854
01:09:09,670 --> 01:09:13,340
(With such a large pasture, the manure is scattered everywhere.)

1855
01:09:13,510 --> 01:09:16,680
Each person grabs a snow shovel...

1856
01:09:17,110 --> 01:09:18,780
and scoops it up.

1857
01:09:18,880 --> 01:09:20,880
We'll fill the one-ton truck by the end of the day.

1858
01:09:20,980 --> 01:09:22,049
- Fill that truck?
- Yes.

1859
01:09:22,050 --> 01:09:24,850
We'll take it to the compost area and unload it.

1860
01:09:25,150 --> 01:09:27,119
Think of it as picking up fallen leaves.

1861
01:09:27,120 --> 01:09:28,120
Yes, sir.

1862
01:09:28,790 --> 01:09:30,820
It's hard to tell apart from the rocks.

1863
01:09:33,560 --> 01:09:35,559
The manure stopped bothering me at some point.

1864
01:09:35,560 --> 01:09:37,160
Why would you get a close shot of this?

1865
01:09:37,630 --> 01:09:39,330
Why would you get a close shot of manure?

1866
01:09:40,100 --> 01:09:41,600
Why are you filming me after the manure?

1867
01:09:42,100 --> 01:09:45,369
(It just happened that way.)

1868
01:09:45,370 --> 01:09:47,970
Compared to cow poop, horse poop looks cute.

1869
01:09:48,640 --> 01:09:50,310
Cow poop is basically diarrhea, isn't it?

1870
01:09:50,710 --> 01:09:51,750
Goodness.

1871
01:09:52,310 --> 01:09:53,849
Tell me when you see poop. What's this?

1872
01:09:53,850 --> 01:09:54,850
This is poop too.

1873
01:09:56,250 --> 01:09:59,719
(Picking up horse manure hidden among the grass)

1874
01:09:59,720 --> 01:10:01,389
(Looking around)

1875
01:10:01,390 --> 01:10:03,090
You know what? Kwang Soo.

1876
01:10:03,190 --> 01:10:04,190
What?

1877
01:10:05,330 --> 01:10:07,290
- You know what I feel already?
- Yes.

1878
01:10:07,630 --> 01:10:09,660
- Finding nicely shaped ones...
- Yes.

1879
01:10:10,130 --> 01:10:11,160
feels satisfying.

1880
01:10:12,170 --> 01:10:13,230
Poop makes you feel satisfied?

1881
01:10:14,430 --> 01:10:15,700
I wouldn't go that far.

1882
01:10:17,040 --> 01:10:19,510
This one is a giant.

1883
01:10:19,670 --> 01:10:22,180
(Scraping)

1884
01:10:22,280 --> 01:10:24,979
(The trainees focus on picking up horse manure.)

1885
01:10:24,980 --> 01:10:26,150
This is a gold mine of poop.

1886
01:10:27,210 --> 01:10:30,179
(He hit the horse manure jackpot.)

1887
01:10:30,180 --> 01:10:32,590
It's like a rock.

1888
01:10:33,320 --> 01:10:34,690
Seriously. Take a look at this.

1889
01:10:36,260 --> 01:10:38,389
- Like a pebble?
- Yes, it's like a pebble.

1890
01:10:38,390 --> 01:10:39,390
(Kyung Soo picks it up like it's a pebble.)

1891
01:10:39,530 --> 01:10:43,599
They only poop around the edge of their territory.

1892
01:10:43,600 --> 01:10:46,169
(You keep analyzing poop, aren't you?)

1893
01:10:46,170 --> 01:10:47,570
All we do is clean up poop.

1894
01:10:48,200 --> 01:10:49,670
I might as well analyze it...

1895
01:10:50,200 --> 01:10:51,969
to see how it's different from cow manure.

1896
01:10:51,970 --> 01:10:52,970
It was still fun.

1897
01:10:53,240 --> 01:10:56,040
You don't get a chance to learn...

1898
01:10:56,440 --> 01:10:59,010
how different cow manure and horse manure really are.

1899
01:10:59,450 --> 01:11:00,680
It was a new discovery.

1900
01:11:01,510 --> 01:11:02,879
I'll try to get closer to the horses.

1901
01:11:02,880 --> 01:11:04,449
(He learns something new again.)

1902
01:11:04,450 --> 01:11:05,620
You know what?

1903
01:11:06,990 --> 01:11:08,290
Whoever loses rock-paper-scissors...

1904
01:11:09,160 --> 01:11:11,320
The winner tries to toss it into the loser's mouth from a distance.

1905
01:11:11,760 --> 01:11:13,760
I can really do it.

1906
01:11:14,490 --> 01:11:15,500
What?

1907
01:11:15,760 --> 01:11:17,000
While standing apart like this,

1908
01:11:17,200 --> 01:11:18,529
the loser of rock-paper-scissors does this.

1909
01:11:18,530 --> 01:11:19,699
(Opening wide)

1910
01:11:19,700 --> 01:11:22,269
The winner throws it into the loser's mouth.

1911
01:11:22,270 --> 01:11:23,300
He only gets one chance.

1912
01:11:24,100 --> 01:11:25,140
- I'm in.
- Just one round.

1913
01:11:25,910 --> 01:11:27,939
(They start a feed poop game in the middle of work.)

1914
01:11:27,940 --> 01:11:29,039
What CEO Kim touched...

1915
01:11:29,040 --> 01:11:31,510
Ready or not, rock-paper-scissors.

1916
01:11:31,769 --> 01:11:33,150
- Darn it.
- Okay.

1917
01:11:33,750 --> 01:11:35,579
(Kwang Soo wins.)

1918
01:11:35,580 --> 01:11:38,449
(Speechless)

1919
01:11:38,450 --> 01:11:41,319
(Which one shall I throw?)

1920
01:11:41,320 --> 01:11:42,420
This is mostly grass.

1921
01:11:44,120 --> 01:11:45,960
Hey, it's a Dubai chewy cookie.

1922
01:11:47,490 --> 01:11:48,829
(It looks almost like a Dubai chewy cookie.)

1923
01:11:48,830 --> 01:11:50,299
You have to stand next to that container.

1924
01:11:50,300 --> 01:11:52,099
You're too close.

1925
01:11:52,100 --> 01:11:53,869
- You said that you'd do it there.
- It won't move.

1926
01:11:53,870 --> 01:11:55,539
- Do it over there.
- It won't move at all.

1927
01:11:55,540 --> 01:11:56,839
- It won't move at all.
- It will.

1928
01:11:56,840 --> 01:11:58,340
- It's only grass.
- It will move.

1929
01:11:58,540 --> 01:12:00,269
You said that you'd stand next to the red container.

1930
01:12:00,270 --> 01:12:01,739
How can I throw it into your mouth from there?

1931
01:12:01,740 --> 01:12:04,539
You'll be throwing poop. You must stand at least that far.

1932
01:12:04,540 --> 01:12:05,879
I can't move any farther.

1933
01:12:05,880 --> 01:12:06,980
Move back a little more.

1934
01:12:07,080 --> 01:12:08,980
Also, you can only throw it like this.

1935
01:12:09,080 --> 01:12:10,120
Like this?

1936
01:12:10,180 --> 01:12:11,690
I won't make it this way. Open up.

1937
01:12:12,720 --> 01:12:15,289
(Kyung Soo complains, but still opens his mouth.)

1938
01:12:15,290 --> 01:12:16,390
Don't move.

1939
01:12:17,320 --> 01:12:19,559
(Getting into position)

1940
01:12:19,753 --> 01:12:20,630
Please.

1941
01:12:21,390 --> 01:12:23,200
(Waiting like a goalpost)

1942
01:12:23,960 --> 01:12:26,500
(Will he make the shot from this far away?)

1943
01:12:27,630 --> 01:12:29,900
(The horse chewy cookie is thrown.)

1944
01:12:30,040 --> 01:12:32,540
(Please miss.)

1945
01:12:33,610 --> 01:12:36,310
(Please go into his mouth.)

1946
01:12:36,610 --> 01:12:39,310
(What will happen to the horse chewy cookie?)

1947
01:12:40,910 --> 01:12:42,920
(He hits it right away.)

1948
01:12:43,250 --> 01:12:45,519
(There you go.)

1949
01:12:45,520 --> 01:12:48,219
(I almost had it.)

1950
01:12:48,220 --> 01:12:49,419
(It started like basketball, but ended like baseball.)

1951
01:12:49,420 --> 01:12:50,519
Nice shot.

1952
01:12:50,520 --> 01:12:52,059
(It started like basketball, but ended like baseball.)

1953
01:12:52,060 --> 01:12:54,990
(Let's just go back to work.)

1954
01:12:55,100 --> 01:12:57,630
The atmosphere is clearly different from the last place we visited.

1955
01:12:58,260 --> 01:13:00,370
The last place was nice in its own way,

1956
01:13:01,330 --> 01:13:03,100
but this one is more... How shall I put it?

1957
01:13:06,410 --> 01:13:07,410
Hey.

1958
01:13:07,640 --> 01:13:08,640
Hey!

1959
01:13:08,641 --> 01:13:09,709
(Kyung Soo gets mischievous.)

1960
01:13:09,816 --> 01:13:11,286
What's the matter?

1961
01:13:11,580 --> 01:13:13,549
- This is mine.
- We're working together.

1962
01:13:13,550 --> 01:13:15,280
We're loading one ton together.

1963
01:13:15,550 --> 01:13:17,319
(Teasing Kwang Soo just like always)

1964
01:13:17,320 --> 01:13:19,250
Where are you going? We have to clean up here.

1965
01:13:19,490 --> 01:13:21,790
We don't have time. The sun is going down soon.

1966
01:13:23,120 --> 01:13:26,190
(Kwang Soo manages to toss it into Kyung Soo's cart.)

1967
01:13:26,930 --> 01:13:27,632
My gosh.

1968
01:13:28,560 --> 01:13:32,130
(Suddenly, a horse starts to run.)

1969
01:13:32,330 --> 01:13:33,330
That looks cool.

1970
01:13:36,170 --> 01:13:37,600
That looks cool. I wonder how he feels.

1971
01:13:38,570 --> 01:13:39,870
I guess he wants to run.

1972
01:13:42,440 --> 01:13:45,150
(He runs, showing his career as a former racehorse.)

1973
01:13:45,280 --> 01:13:46,580
He's really fast.

1974
01:13:48,150 --> 01:13:49,379
(Glancing)

1975
01:13:49,380 --> 01:13:50,480
Shall I give him a tangerine?

1976
01:13:51,650 --> 01:13:54,089
(After a good run, he's taking a break.)

1977
01:13:54,090 --> 01:13:57,959
(He approaches with a secret weapon.)

1978
01:13:57,960 --> 01:14:00,290
(Sneaking up quietly)

1979
01:14:03,560 --> 01:14:06,369
(The moment he sees it, he eagerly takes the tangerine.)

1980
01:14:06,370 --> 01:14:07,770
It looks like he's feeling better.

1981
01:14:09,640 --> 01:14:10,869
You wanted to do something with animals.

1982
01:14:10,870 --> 01:14:13,039
It looks like you're already bonding with one.

1983
01:14:13,040 --> 01:14:14,709
Kwang Soo, clean up the poop.

1984
01:14:14,710 --> 01:14:15,780
Wait.

1985
01:14:16,180 --> 01:14:17,839
- He's not feeling so well.
- Kwang Soo.

1986
01:14:17,840 --> 01:14:18,849
Kwang Soo.

1987
01:14:18,850 --> 01:14:20,449
(Using the horse's mood as an excuse to put off work)

1988
01:14:20,450 --> 01:14:21,879
They really look like pebbles.

1989
01:14:21,880 --> 01:14:24,619
(They really look like pebbles.)

1990
01:14:24,620 --> 01:14:26,719
(Kyung Soo picks up the pebbles diligently.)

1991
01:14:26,720 --> 01:14:29,020
You have to scratch him hard to make him pleasant.

1992
01:14:29,560 --> 01:14:31,559
(Approaching quietly)

1993
01:14:31,560 --> 01:14:33,789
You have to scratch him very hard.

1994
01:14:33,790 --> 01:14:35,030
(He walks over as if asking for a head scratch.)

1995
01:14:37,360 --> 01:14:38,400
Put your mane back.

1996
01:14:39,830 --> 01:14:41,030
He seems to like it.

1997
01:14:41,900 --> 01:14:43,000
He seems to love it.

1998
01:14:44,770 --> 01:14:47,510
It rubs against people like a cat.

1999
01:14:47,770 --> 01:14:48,779
Isn't it refreshing?

2000
01:14:48,780 --> 01:14:50,910
The horse really likes it.

2001
01:14:51,240 --> 01:14:53,909
(Keeping it happily entertained)

2002
01:14:53,910 --> 01:14:55,750
Kyung Soo, what are you doing instead of picking up poop?

2003
01:14:55,980 --> 01:14:57,320
You should work like Kwang Soo.

2004
01:14:57,620 --> 01:15:00,190
(The boss appears.)

2005
01:15:00,290 --> 01:15:01,290
Kyung Soo.

2006
01:15:01,990 --> 01:15:03,990
Please focus. We aren't here to have fun.

2007
01:15:04,420 --> 01:15:07,159
(Meanwhile, Kwang Soo is already back at work.)

2008
01:15:07,160 --> 01:15:09,559
(Indignant)

2009
01:15:09,560 --> 01:15:14,470
(He only just started bonding with a horse.)

2010
01:15:14,570 --> 01:15:16,100
Should we load them on the truck?

2011
01:15:17,470 --> 01:15:19,740
Gosh, you got a lot there.

2012
01:15:20,410 --> 01:15:21,439
Didn't we get quite a lot?

2013
01:15:21,440 --> 01:15:22,510
Yes, well done.

2014
01:15:22,840 --> 01:15:24,939
This will be enough to earn 40 dollars.

2015
01:15:24,940 --> 01:15:26,079
Really?

2016
01:15:26,080 --> 01:15:27,750
Do you want to try listing on Karrot?

2017
01:15:28,580 --> 01:15:30,150
You never know. You could get a message.

2018
01:15:30,320 --> 01:15:31,990
- Sure.
- Can you drive this truck?

2019
01:15:32,490 --> 01:15:34,289
- I can drive it.
- I'll teach you.

2020
01:15:34,290 --> 01:15:37,020
I'm sorry, Sung Joon. This is your part-time job.

2021
01:15:37,460 --> 01:15:39,290
Are you in charge of this?

2022
01:15:39,860 --> 01:15:41,789
- Doesn't the poop look different?
- You're right.

2023
01:15:41,790 --> 01:15:43,630
- If it's worth 40 dollars...
- It's basically money.

2024
01:15:44,130 --> 01:15:45,159
I'll take this side.

2025
01:15:45,160 --> 01:15:46,170
I'll take this side.

2026
01:15:46,330 --> 01:15:48,130
Place it on here.

2027
01:15:48,500 --> 01:15:49,540
And push it in.

2028
01:15:51,440 --> 01:15:52,869
- Hey.
- Oh, no.

2029
01:15:52,870 --> 01:15:54,909
- Twenty, thirty dollars.
- We're spilling money.

2030
01:15:54,910 --> 01:15:56,039
(The horse manure spills onto the ground.)

2031
01:15:56,040 --> 01:15:57,210
(Piles of cash scatter everywhere.)

2032
01:15:57,310 --> 01:15:58,310
Watch it, Sung Joon.

2033
01:15:59,480 --> 01:16:01,249
We spent one hour collecting this.

2034
01:16:01,250 --> 01:16:02,779
(Embarrassed)

2035
01:16:02,780 --> 01:16:03,780
I knew it.

2036
01:16:04,680 --> 01:16:05,689
A moment ago...

2037
01:16:05,690 --> 01:16:06,849
(We can't leave anything behind.)

2038
01:16:06,850 --> 01:16:09,660
(While he's at it, he takes photos for the marketplace listing.)

2039
01:16:09,860 --> 01:16:10,860
Okay.

2040
01:16:11,760 --> 01:16:13,129
Why don't you take a photo with the horse in it?

2041
01:16:13,130 --> 01:16:14,759
With Arthur in the frame.

2042
01:16:14,760 --> 01:16:15,760
Yes, take a photo with the horse.

2043
01:16:15,761 --> 01:16:18,360
(If we're doing it, we might as well do it properly.)

2044
01:16:18,570 --> 01:16:19,870
Make sure you get me from behind.

2045
01:16:21,300 --> 01:16:23,870
(With meticulous direction)

2046
01:16:23,970 --> 01:16:26,610
(Very serious)

2047
01:16:26,770 --> 01:16:27,770
Okay.

2048
01:16:28,310 --> 01:16:29,380
It came out well.

2049
01:16:30,010 --> 01:16:31,610
There's no way this won't sell.

2050
01:16:32,950 --> 01:16:34,280
There's no way it won't sell.

2051
01:16:34,480 --> 01:16:35,480
First,

2052
01:16:35,920 --> 01:16:36,979
bond with the horse...

2053
01:16:36,980 --> 01:16:38,079
- you're assigned to...
- Yes.

2054
01:16:38,080 --> 01:16:40,020
before we leave.

2055
01:16:40,620 --> 01:16:41,689
What's his name?

2056
01:16:41,690 --> 01:16:42,759
John Snow.

2057
01:16:42,760 --> 01:16:45,460
Before coming to our ranch, Snow had earned...

2058
01:16:45,690 --> 01:16:47,590
the most prize money of any horse here.

2059
01:16:47,890 --> 01:16:48,899
He won races?

2060
01:16:48,900 --> 01:16:50,499
Yes, he was a racehorse.

2061
01:16:50,500 --> 01:16:52,599
- I see.
- He won 269,000 dollars.

2062
01:16:52,600 --> 01:16:53,669
My gosh.

2063
01:16:53,670 --> 01:16:56,170
Even after earning all that money,

2064
01:16:56,640 --> 01:16:58,239
he was about to be sent somewhere terrible.

2065
01:16:58,240 --> 01:16:59,240
(John Snow was at risk of being euthanized.)

2066
01:16:59,241 --> 01:17:00,740
We rescued him...

2067
01:17:01,140 --> 01:17:02,609
and brought him here.

2068
01:17:02,610 --> 01:17:05,310
John Snow is Kwang Soo's horse.

2069
01:17:05,550 --> 01:17:06,579
(Kwang Soo's partner horse is John Snow.)

2070
01:17:06,580 --> 01:17:09,049
- So you will take him.
- Okay.

2071
01:17:09,050 --> 01:17:11,279
He's a Jeju Halla horse.

2072
01:17:11,280 --> 01:17:13,589
He retired from Jeju Racecourse in 2021.

2073
01:17:13,590 --> 01:17:14,920
The problem was that he was too tall.

2074
01:17:15,490 --> 01:17:17,320
A Jeju Halla horse can't be taller than 137cm.

2075
01:17:17,790 --> 01:17:19,290
So they kept trimming down his hooves.

2076
01:17:19,560 --> 01:17:20,929
They eventually damaged a nerve.

2077
01:17:20,930 --> 01:17:23,860
It made him lame, so he had to retire.

2078
01:17:24,830 --> 01:17:27,370
Kyung Soo, you're assigned to Morris.

2079
01:17:27,970 --> 01:17:29,800
We prepared these two horses for you.

2080
01:17:30,540 --> 01:17:32,539
Watch carefully. When I walk,

2081
01:17:32,540 --> 01:17:34,470
the horse matches my stride like this.

2082
01:17:35,110 --> 01:17:35,776
Achick.

2083
01:17:36,110 --> 01:17:37,379
(The ranch owner demonstrates a leading exercise.)

2084
01:17:37,380 --> 01:17:38,850
"Achick."

2085
01:17:39,680 --> 01:17:40,680
- You have to say it the same.
- That was nice.

2086
01:17:40,681 --> 01:17:42,019
(Imitating the boss's cue)

2087
01:17:42,020 --> 01:17:44,279
- "Oh chick." Wasn't that too much?
- If you come across...

2088
01:17:44,280 --> 01:17:46,950
- some nice grass, give him some.
- Yes.

2089
01:17:47,050 --> 01:17:48,590
- Try it, Kwang Soo.
- Yes, sir.

2090
01:17:49,460 --> 01:17:51,389
- Achick.
- All right. Show your back.

2091
01:17:51,390 --> 01:17:53,759
(Kwang Soo takes the lead confidently.)

2092
01:17:53,760 --> 01:17:55,899
- Say it again.
- Achick.

2093
01:17:55,900 --> 01:17:59,470
(He loses control immediately.)

2094
01:17:59,570 --> 01:18:02,140
- Achick.
- Turn around. Keep going.

2095
01:18:02,470 --> 01:18:03,094
Achick.

2096
01:18:05,140 --> 01:18:06,240
Run faster.

2097
01:18:07,210 --> 01:18:09,810
(A big match between the giraffe and the horse)

2098
01:18:11,540 --> 01:18:12,779
(Trying to take the lead across the vast pasture)

2099
01:18:12,780 --> 01:18:13,850
That's good.

2100
01:18:14,510 --> 01:18:15,980
This is very exciting.

2101
01:18:16,620 --> 01:18:17,620
Achick!

2102
01:18:19,290 --> 01:18:21,789
(Exhausted)

2103
01:18:21,790 --> 01:18:24,789
(They look like they're in sync.)

2104
01:18:24,790 --> 01:18:26,030
Stop.

2105
01:18:26,090 --> 01:18:27,159
My goodness.

2106
01:18:27,160 --> 01:18:28,959
(Flopping down)

2107
01:18:28,960 --> 01:18:31,900
(Bonding or not, Kwang Soo gets ditched.)

2108
01:18:32,630 --> 01:18:35,499
(Bonding with a horse isn't easy.)

2109
01:18:35,500 --> 01:18:38,940
(Will the trainees be able to build a bond with their partner?)

2110
01:18:39,070 --> 01:18:41,469
(He totally ignores me.)

2111
01:18:41,470 --> 01:18:44,639
(Kwang Soo in a one-sided love with a horse)

2112
01:18:44,640 --> 01:18:45,649
(You're so cute.)

2113
01:18:45,650 --> 01:18:47,149
(How are you so cute?)

2114
01:18:47,150 --> 01:18:49,520
(Kyung Soo meets his true love.)

2115
01:18:49,680 --> 01:18:52,949
(The peaceful ranch life continues.)

2116
01:18:52,950 --> 01:18:55,249
(Don't go!)

2117
01:18:55,250 --> 01:18:56,920
(No, come this way.)

2118
01:18:57,220 --> 01:18:59,030
(They run when they want to run.)

2119
01:18:59,090 --> 01:19:00,890
(Why is he lying down all of a sudden?)

2120
01:19:01,430 --> 01:19:03,759
(These free-spirited horses lie down when they want to.)

2121
01:19:03,760 --> 01:19:06,500
(Compared to cows, horses are much harder to care for.)

2122
01:19:06,930 --> 01:19:09,869
(Because of that, the work keeps piling up.)

2123
01:19:09,870 --> 01:19:12,709
(Suddenly, I miss Gogo and Farmfarm so much.)

2124
01:19:12,710 --> 01:19:13,939
(I feel paralyzed.)

2125
01:19:13,940 --> 01:19:16,080
(What happened at the horse ranch that makes him want to run away?)

2126
01:19:16,540 --> 01:19:18,579
(That's not an old lady picking bracken, is it?)

2127
01:19:18,580 --> 01:19:19,709
(Who is it?)

2128
01:19:19,710 --> 01:19:21,980
(A stranger appears at the ranch.)

2129
01:19:22,480 --> 01:19:24,179
(She's filming us.)

2130
01:19:24,180 --> 01:19:27,050
(Shoving a camera in everyone's face)

2131
01:19:27,650 --> 01:19:29,560
(Causing a ruckus at the ranch)

2132
01:19:30,620 --> 01:19:32,160
(The atmosphere grows more and more serious.)

2133
01:19:33,260 --> 01:19:37,930
(Who is this mysterious stranger that has everyone confused?)

2134
01:19:39,070 --> 01:19:42,029
(GBRB: Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)

2135
01:19:42,030 --> 01:19:44,599
(Lee Kwang Soo)

2136
01:19:44,600 --> 01:19:46,839
(Kim Woo Bin)

2137
01:19:46,840 --> 01:19:49,010
(Doh Kyung Soo)

2138
01:19:53,510 --> 01:19:56,050
(GBRB: Farm Operation - Go Go Farm)
